<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Sells State-Owned Oil company </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government stroke a
deal with Shell Oil Company Thursday on selling of Rwanda's
government-run oil company, Petrorwanda, to the company.
</P>
<P>
According to the deal, Shell Oil Company acquired 19 out of 32
retail service stations previously owned by Petrorwanda, Donald
Kaberuka, Rwandan Minister for Finance and Economic Planning
indicated.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the government agreed to lease the Gatsata Depots,
15 km northeast of the capital Kigali, for a period of 30 years,
the Rwanda News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Government shares in Petrorwanda have been divested at 2.1
million U.S.

dollars, whereas the annual lease for Gatsata depots was valued at
51,000 dollars,'' Kaberuka said.
</P>
<P>
Paul Maes, Shell Managing Director, based in Kampala declared
that his company will inject 5 million dollars in the
rehabilitation of the Petrorwanda network.
</P>
<P>
"The sale of the company's assets stems from the heavy losses
that have always been incurred,'' explained Kaberuka.
''Petrorwanda owes the government an outstanding debt of over 3,9
million dollars as indicated by December 1998 audit," he
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
He said that Petrorwanda started with specific objectives but
later became a financial liability due to corrupt management and
inefficiency.
</P>
<P>
Kaberuka commended Shell Oil Company for its track record
worldwide, saying "Rwandans hope Shell will bring high level of
services, quality, and competition.''
</P>
<P>
Shell is an international oil company with 60 percent of shares
owned by the Netherlands, while 40 percent belong to the British
government.
</P>
<P>
The divestiture of government's shares in Petrorwanda coincided
with the spectacular rise of fuel pump prices Wednesday which had
seriously disrupted transport of people and goods between the
capital and upcountry.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
