<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Central Bank Staff Threaten to Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Workers at the Reserve Bank of
Zimbabwe Thursday said they have resolved to go on strike over a
45-percent cost of living adjustment across the board to cushion
them against harsh economic conditions.
</P>
<P>
The Workers Union has written a letter to the bank Governor
Leonard Tsumba saying the employees had unanimously resolved to
strike following lack of progress in the collective bargaining
discussions by the Workers Union.
</P>
<P>
The union said while management maintained that cost of living
increase would be given to those considered to have salaries
within salary scales, the workers' position was that the increase
should be across the board.
</P>
<P>
In other words, the union said, management's position was that
the increase should be based on minimums, while workers maintained
that it should be based on actual situations.
</P>
<P>
"If increases are awarded in terms of the management proposal,
it means the majority of workers would receive increases which are
below 45 percent, with a number of workers receiving no increase
at all.
</P>
<P>
To put it simply, management is proposing an increase based on
a zero percent to 45 percent sliding scale," the union said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
