<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Arrests Italian National for Forgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan security forces Tuesday
arrested an Italian for forgery and use of forgeries, the
Prosecutor's Office in Kigali said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
''Elio Mufatti, was netted by the Kigali police following
intensive investigation into reports that he was in possession of
many stamps that attracted people's curiosity,'' Emmanuel
Rukangira, the Kigali Prosecutor disclosed to Rwanda News Agency.
</P>
<P>
Rukangira exhibited 17 different stamps forged by Mufatti which
were found to be copies of some government-owned enterprises like
the Education Ministry printery, some oil companies, and many
hardware shops.
</P>
<P>
The Italian is said to own a fleet of five vehicles which have
 diplomatic plates from Uganda which he was reportedly using to
ferry goods from Uganda to Rwanda without any hindrance at the
customs on the border between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the man explained himself arguing that he was
using the stamps to justify the money donated by the Italian
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Luigi Scotto, the Italian Charges d'Affaires with residence in
Kampala who happened to be at the Prosecutor's office declared
that he was awaiting for an official reply from the Rwandan
government regarding the accusations leveled against his national.
</P>
<P>
''I'm aware of the affair, but the Rwandan Ministry of Foreign
Affairs must give us a verbal note explaining the charges,''
Scotto said, adding that Mufatti does not enjoy a diplomatic
status.
</P>
<P>
Mufatti, 45, has been working in the Italian cooperation since
1995. He is now remanded in Kigali Central Prison. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
