<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Declares Unilateral Cease-fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government Thursday
announced a unilateral comprehensive cease-fire in all fronts all
over the country to facilitate relief operations in the country's
war-torn south.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire is to take effect at midnight (2200 GMT)
Thursday and last until October 15, said the Sudanese foreign
ministry in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The government expressed the hope that John Garang, leader of
the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA), will follow the
suit to end the people's sufferings and speed up an overall
solution.
</P>
<P>
The SPLA is a major rebel group fighting the government forces
in southern Sudan for autonomy since 1983 and used to stage
military operations against government troops in the
August-October autumn season of heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
The statement reiterated the government's determination to
shoulder its responsibilities for the people and to seek a
peaceful solution to the issue.
</P>
<P>
The statement was released following comments by Foreign
Minister Mustafa Osman Ismail denying allegations that the
Sudanese government used chemical weapons in southern Sudan.
</P>
</TEXT>
