<HEADLINE> Angolan Child Patients to Get Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 5 (xinhua) -- Angolan child patients in Benguela
City will get two million U.S. dollars' worth of food and
medicaments in support, Keith Simons, head of the U.S.
International Development Agency (USAID), announced Thursday in
Angola.
</P>
<P>
Simons, on a visit to Benguela, an important harbor city in
Angola, said that from September, some 300 child patients under 10
years old in the Nutrition Center of Benguela Central Hospital
will benefit from the USAID supporting plan.
</P>
<P>
Simons also said that the U.S. government hopes that the
safety of road transportation can be guaranteed, so that the
humanitarian aids can be effectively sent to children in need in
other cities.
</P>
<P>
The USAID mission will meet with officials of the Angolan Armed
Forces (FAA) in Benguela.
</P>
<P>
Simons will also visit other main cities in Angola for
consultation and an appraisal of the humanitarian situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
