<HEADLINE> Britain Writes off Zambia's Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain has written off Zambia's
46 million British pound debt, British Ambassador to Lusaka Thomas
Young announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The remaining 65 million pound Zambia owes to Britain has been
rescheduled and will be paid off after six years over a period of
24 years.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Finance Minister Katele Kalumba said that Britain's
move will lessen Zambia's external debt service obligations and
enable the Zambian government to finance in other economic sectors
and thus help alleviate poverty of Zambians.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that delayed sale of the Zambia Consolidated
Copper Mines (ZCCM) and low agricultural output affect his
country's economic performance.
</P>
<P>
To revive its gloomy copper industry, the copper-producing
country is selling its copper mines to private hands, foreign
investors in particular.
</P>
<P>
But due to disagreement over the sale, bigger mines have not
been sold out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
