<HEADLINE> S. Africa's Business Confidence Resumes Despite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's business
confidence index (BCI) has continued to rise strongly on a new
wave of economic optimism in July despite the effects of the fall
of the gold price, South African Chamber of Business (Sacob) said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The index rose by 3.1 points, the sharpest rise this year, from
87 in June to 90.1.
</P>
<P>
This is up from an all-time low of 83 at the beginning of the
year. The current levels are similar to figures experienced in
1992. The index rose to a record of 105 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
A positive reading was largely in response to interest rate
cuts, Sacob said.
</P>
<P>
But it warned not to expect too much from the banks in the near
future. A positive reading was largely in response to interest
rate cuts, Sacob said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to Sacob, the stability of the rand also played a
role in producing an upswing of continued positive sentiment in
the business community.
</P>
<P>
"Financial stability is more firmly entrenched than a year ago.
 Improving levels of foreign confidence have been sustained," said
chief executive officer Kevin Wakeford.
</P>
<P>
He said although domestic demand was already showing signs of
moving out of the doldrums, the initial stages of an economic
recovery may be mainly export-led.
</P>
<P>
Gold's recent nose-dive, he added, had not yet produced the
wake of devastation that some had been predicting, due to the
metals declining predominance in South Africa's economy.
</P>
<P>
"The show of optimism to some extent has countered the negative
effects of the serious decline of the gold price," said Wakeford.
</P>
<P>
The rise in business confidence has emanated mainly from the
manufacturing sector, which according to the BCI has been
demonstrating a positive trend.
</P>
<P>
Sales volumes of manufactured goods are expected to rise over
the next 12 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
