<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 2000GMT, Thursday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIYADH -- A senior Saudi official has denied that Saudi Arabia
is seeking to obtain nuclear weapons from Pakistan or other
countries.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Second Deputy Premier Prince Sultan Ibn Abdul-Aziz said
his country is a signatory of the Nuclear Non-proliferation
Treaty and committed to its international obligations, the
London-based Saudi daily Al Charq Al Awsat reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan, who is also minister of Defense and Aviation,
asserted that Saudi Arabia hopes to see the region free of all
mass destruction weapons, including nuclear arms.
(BC-Saudi Arabia-Weapons)
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak finished the
expansion of his cabinet Thursday by appointing five new ministers
from left and center coalition parties.
</P>
<P>
The 120-member Knesset, or parliament, approved the
appointments of the new ministers and eight deputy ministers by a
vote of 52-16 with eight abstentions. (BC-Israel-Cabinet)
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran threatened here on Thursday to act with power if
the Taliban fails to identify and punish the killers of its
diplomats and correspondent in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
"We will not rest until we get a satisfactory answer," Iranian
Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi said while speaking to the
victims' families on the first anniversary of their deaths.
</P>
<P>
Eight Iranian diplomats and a correspondent of the official
Islamic Republic News Agency (IRNA) were killed a year ago when
the Taliban troops took over Mazar-e-Sharif, a strategic town in
northern Afghanistan, from opposition forces.
(BC-Iran-Afghanistan-Taliban)
</P>
<P>
KHARTOUM -- The Sudanese government Thursday announced a
unilateral comprehensive cease-fire in all fronts all over the
country to facilitate relief operations in the country's war-torn
south.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire is to take effect at midnight (2200 GMT)
Thursday and last until October 15, said the Sudanese foreign
ministry in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The government expressed the hope that John Garang, leader of
the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA), will follow the
suit to end the people's sufferings and speed up an overall
solution. (BC-Sudan-Cease-fire) 
</P>
</TEXT>
