<HEADLINE> Mozambicans Urged to Eradicate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique's Cultural, Youth and
Sports Deputy Minister Joel Libombo called on the whole society to
be united in their struggle to uproot poverty in the country.
</P>
<P>
Libombo made the call at a press conference for the launching
of an anti- poverty semi-marathon to be held in October in the
southern African country.
</P>
<P>
The biggest problem facing Mozambicans are poverty, he said,
adding that various sector of the society, including the sport
sector, should join hands against poverty.
</P>
<P>
Sports can be used to encourage people to fight against
poverty, so the whole nation should give enough attention to
sports, he said.
</P>
<P>
Like before, money raised from the 1999 marathon is to be used
to support the homeless children in the country.
</P>
<P>
The marathon will be held in central Mozambique's Beira and
northern Nampula cities respectively on October 3 and October 17.
</P>
<P>
The activity is jointly sponsored by the United Nations
Development Program, the Mozambican Athletic Association and some
other organizations.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations has launched an anti-poverty week each year
to raise people's awareness to fight poverty. This year's
anti-poverty week is scheduled for October 18 to 24.
</P>
<P>
The southern African country has a population of 16 million,
with over 60 percent people living under poverty line.  
</P>
</TEXT>
