<HEADLINE> U.S. Senate OKs Holbrooke as U.N. Ambassador </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. Senate Thursday
confirmed Richard Holbrooke as U.N. ambassador after the post has
been vacant for almost one year.
</P>
<P>
After a 35-minute debate, the Senate voted 81-16 to approve the
appointment.
</P>
<P>
In June 1998, U.S. President Bill Clinton first announced the
appointment of Holbrooke to replace Bill Richardson. However, the
appointment was bogged dow because of investigations into
Holbrooke's business contacts.
</P>
<P>
Since Richardson left the U.N. post in September, the United
States launched airstrikes against both Iraq and Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke, 58, is the Clinton administrator's top international
troubleshooter and the architect of the 1995 Bosnia agreement
</P>
<P>
An Associated Press report said that Holbrooke was a
"contender" for secretary of state in Clinton's second term before
the president chose Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
The report also said he has been at odds at times with Albright
and is a favorite target for Republicans since he's widely viewed
as a likely secretary of state if Vice President Al Gore wins the
presidency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
