<HEADLINE> Assad Replies Clinton's Letter on Peace Talks with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Syrian President Hafez
al-Assad has replied to President Bill Clinton on resumption of
peace talks between Syria and Israel, the White House said on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
President Assad's letter was received on Wednesday at the White
House, which was in response to last month letter, in which
Clinton urged Assad to "seize the moment of opportunity" and
negotiate peace terms with Israel's newly elected prime minister,
Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
"The president received a reply," White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart told reporters. "He was pleased to receive it, but I'm no
going to go into the substance of the letter." Lockhart added.
</P>
<P>
According to some U.S. officials, the administration was
"studying the response" from the Syrian president.
</P>
<P>
"He wants the United States to be involved in the process," one
of the officials said. "It is a continuing process. And the
president said we will remain in close communication."
</P>
<P>
Barak, who took the place of Benjamin Netanyahu early last
month following hie victory in the May 17 election, visited
Washington after his assumption of the premiership and held talks
with Clinton on ways of revival of stalled the peace process in
the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
He has publicly promised to make a "painful compromise" with
Syria over the Golan Heights, which was seized by Israel during
the 1967 Arab-Israeli war.
</P>
<P>
Syria initially responded favorably to Barak's overtures. But
it has recently taken a more pessimistic tone. On Wednesday
Syria's foreign minister said no date was yet set for the
resumption of peace talks that broke off in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
