<HEADLINE> U.S. House Passes Tax Cut Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- U.S. House of Representatives
passed a 10-year, 792 billion dollars tax cut bill introduced by
the Republican party Thursday in spite of repeated veto threats
from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The vote was 221-206 to send the bill to the Senate, where
expected final passage was scheduled for this evening.
</P>
<P>
"We have a good deal for the American people," Speaker Dennis
Hastert said. "It's fair, responsible and balanced tax-relief
bill."
</P>
<P>
Clinton, addressing a Democratic rally at the Capitol before
the vote, said any budget surplus should go first for preserving
social security and Medicare and reducing government debt.
</P>
<P>
The Republican leaders will send the bill to Clinton for
signature after the August congressional recess to avoid an
immediate veto.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and most Democrats insisted that projected budget
surpluses should be used to first safeguard social security and
Medicare, pay down public debt and ensure adequate levels of
government spending.
</P>
<P>
Although Clinton has said he would sign a modest tax cut of
perhaps 300 billion dollars, Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott
said that he saw no signs of compromise with the White House.
</P>
<P>
Republicans said the projected 2.9 trillion dollars surplus
over the next decade was enough to meet Clinton's priorities and
still enact the largest tax cut since 1981.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
