<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Donates $12.5 Million for Refugees in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The World Food Program
(WFP) Thursday hailed a donation of 12.5 million U.S. dollars from
the European Commission Humanitarian Office, which will be used to
feed some 40,000 foreign refugees in western Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"We are enormously relieved and grateful to get such a generous
response from the European Commission Humanitarian Office," WFP
representative in Tanzania, Irene Lacy, said in a press release
issued in Dar es Salaam.
</P>
<P>
The press release also alerted donors and the public to a
severe funding shortfall, which could lead to a potential gap in
the food aid to the refugees between June and September.
</P>
<P>
It said that to avoid a complete halt in food distributions,
the WFP reduced rations of cereals and pulses for the refugees by
25 percent over a two-month period in Kigoma and Kagera regions in
west Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the latest donations, however, it is planned that
full rations will be resumed this month," the press release noted.
</P>
<P>
It added that the continuing insecurity in neighboring Burundi
and the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) has forced large
number of refugees to cross border into Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
However, the number of refugees has dropped from almost 10,000
people per week in June to 5,000 recently.
</P>
<P>
The WFP has also expressed gratitude to earlier contributions
made by the United States, Denmark, Germany, Sweden and
Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
On top of 400,000 Congolese and Burundian refugees living in
camps in Tanzania, the WFP also provides food aid to 900,000
people in other Great Lakes Region countries like Rwanda and
Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ghana's Universities Risk Closure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Vice chancellors of the Ghanaian
universities said Thursday in Accra, Ghana, that the country's
three universities risk closure or their intakes be reduced due to
lack of financial resources, the Ghana News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"The alternative now is to close down until such time when
adequate financial resources are obtained from sponsors of
students, the government or parents or admit no fresh students and
lay off about 30 percent of continuing students," the Committee of
Vice Chancellors said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The committee, which is in charge of the management and
administration of the universities, said that much as the
institutions do not wish to impose hardships on students, they
cannot run any credible academic programs in the 1999/2000
academic year without additional funding.
</P>
<P>
The universities subsist on government grants to finance their
programs and have had to operate with great difficulty, as the
money provided do not match their financial requirements.
</P>
<P>
Each of them requires between 3.2 million cedis (one U.S.
dollar equals some 2,540 cedis) and 9.5 million cedis to train a
student in humanities, sciences and medicine.
</P>
<P>
The vice chancellors said grants and income from other sources
over the past five years have amounted to less than 60 percent of
(their) requirements.
</P>
<P>
"The shortfalls have serious implications for the delivery of
quality academic programs," they said.
</P>
<P>
This has resulted, "in a serious attack" on the integrity of
degrees awarded by the universities by some employers and
international organizations, "with some of them threatening to
withdraw recognition or accreditation".
</P>
<P>
The committee, therefore, has suggested an increase in the
charge for academic facility user fee to raise adequate resources.
</P>
<P>
"These charges range from 290,000 to 320,000 cedis per student
per year for humanities and 430,000 cedis to 460,000 cedis per
student per year for science and applied science excluding
medicine," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
