<HEADLINE> Russia May Lose Arctic Shipping Lane, Official Warns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia is likely to lose its
Arctic Northern Shipping Lane in five to 10 years unless the
government takes "well-calculated steps," First Deputy Prime
Minister Nikolai Aksyonenko warned Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The icebreakers and northern ports are in poor condition,
Aksyonenko said, noting that the areas served by the lane contain
nearly 35 percent of the world's stores of oil and gas, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Only 1.48 million tons of cargo were shipped along the route
last year, a dramatic drop from 6.58 million tons of 1997, he told
a conference on the status of and outlook for the lane.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the potential is there for 25 million to 30
million tons of oil from the Timan-Pechora province and of the Ob
and Yenisei river basins, 15 million to 20 million tons of
liquefied gas from the Yamal Peninsula and 1.3 million tons of gas
condensate from the Ob and Yenisei river basins to be shipped to
Europe in 2015, Interfax reported. 
</P>
</TEXT>
