resolved to examine the operations of the Electoral Commission,
correspondence between Zambia Independent Monitoring Team and the
National Assembly has revealed.
</P>
<P>
According to parliamentary records available here Thursday,
president of the independent monitoring team, Alfred Zulu, has
confirmed the development but declined to give full details,
saying that his recommendations were now property of the national
assembly.
</P>
<P>
Correspondence from the National Assembly dated on July 1
stated that the committee, according to their program of work for
this year, is resolved to examine the operations of the Electoral
Commission with the help of monitoring team which had reportedly
made recommendations to overhaul the commission.
</P>
<P>
The correspondence from the parliament further requested the
team to submit 20 copies of a detailed memorandum which include
among other things an assessment of information regarding to what
extent are the service provided by the Electoral Commission known
and accessible to the potential users throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Parliament further requested the monitoring team to furnish
details on what measures the Electoral Commission should take to
sensitize the public on its services.
</P>
<P>
On July 27, Zulu submitted a memorandum and requested for some
changes in the operation of the commission.
</P>
<P>
United Party for National Development (UPND) Lusaka province
chairman, Joseph Chilengi, suggested at a press briefing Monday
that the term of office for Electoral Commission chairman should
be reduced from the current five years to one as a way of infusing
competition and hard work in the office. 
</P>
