ambassador announced that the Angolan government delivered a
letter Wednesday to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, "expressly
notifying the decision of the government."
</P>
<P>
Van Dunem added that some issues on U.N.'s "physical presence"
in Angola are currently discussed.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador stressed that the Angolan government has been in
favor of a "not so big" U.N. presence, in correspondence with the
reality of the situation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Considering U.N. as a shield for the rebellious National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA), the Angolan
government demanded a pull-out of the United Nations Observer
Mission in Angola last January, when the government troops
encountered some setbacks in battle-fields in the central
provinces Huambo and Bie.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. mission formally pulled out from the war-torn country
on March 1 this year. Meanwhile, the U.N. expressed a will to
maintain a mediatory organization in Angola.
</P>
<P>
But the Angolan government insisted that this kind of agency
should be established in New York, where the U.N. is
headquartered. 
