<HEADLINE> Taliban Urged to Stop Offensive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council Thursday urged Afghan Taliban forces to stop the
offensive immediately and resume political negotiations under the
U.N. auspices.
</P>
<P>
Council members demanded that the Taliban act in line with the
commitments expressed at the meeting in Tashkent in July,
according to a press statement issued by the council president,
Namibia's Martin Andjaba.
</P>
<P>
Council members appealed for the immediate end of all external
interference and in particular called on those states whose
territories are reportedly being used by Afghan parties to take
measures to prevent such acts, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban forces, who control some 90 percent of Afghanistan,
launched their summer offensive on July 28 to capture the rest of
the country before winter begins. However, they have met strong
resistance from northern opposition forces.
</P>
<P>
The fresh fighting has displaced more people in Afghanistan,
known for one of the biggest refugee sources in the world, with
2.1 million Afghans in Iran and 1.6 million in Pakistan, according
to U.N. figures. 
