<HEADLINE> World No. 1 Samsonov Goes Down to Chinese Teenager </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
EINDHOVEN, Netherlands, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese teenager Ma
Lin produced the biggest upset of the world table tennis championships
as he crushed world No. 1 Vladimir Samsonov of Belarus in a men's
singles fourth rounder on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Chinese always took initiative in attacking and hit
a lot of forehand winners after losing the first set 21-15.
</P>
<P>
When Ma clinched the following two sets, 21-18, 21-13, Samsonov
showed justifiable signs of nerves and made a string of unforced
errors to lose the fourth set 21-16.
</P>
<P>
It was only Ma's second win over Samsonov. He had lost to the lanky
Beralussian three times.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, China's 1995 world champion Kong Linghui romped into the
last eight as he downed Poland's Lucjan Blaszczyk 13-21, 21-8, 21-10,
21-14.
</P>
<P>
Dual Olympic gold medalist Liu Guoliang clinched the third
quarter-final berth for China, beating Frenchman and 1993 world
champion Jean-Philippe Gatien 15-21, 23-21, 21-17, 21-14
</P>
<P>
Two Swedish veterans made the last eight, both after five-game
struggles.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion Jan-Ove Waldner edged out Frenchman Christophe
Legout 21-13, 18-21, 21-19, 16-21, 21-14, while 1991 world champion
Jorg Persson rolled over Chinese lefthander Yan Sen 16-21, 21-13,
21-17, 17-21, 21-14.
</P>
<P>
Frenchman Damien Eloi, who upset world sixth-ranked Chinese Wang
Liqin in the third round, went down to Austrian Werner Schlager 21-19,
21-18, 21-12
</P>
<P>
Two-time World Cup holder Zoran Primorac of Croatia denied Sweden a
third quarter-final spot, beating Peter Karlsson 21-15, 11-21, 21-19,
21-5.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Kim Taek Soo, tipped as the second best penholder
after Liu Guoliang, showed strong pysche in his 19-21, 21-17, 11-21,
21-14, 21-14 thriller against former world No. 1 Jean-Michel Saive of
Belgium.
</P>
<P>
In the quarter-finals on Friday, Ma Lin takes on Asian Games
titlist Kim with two-time world champion Waldner against Kong Linghui.
Primorac meets Schlager as Liu Guoliang vs Persson.
</P>
<P>
China virtually dominated the women's singles event as six Chinese
cruised into the quarter-finals.
</P>
<P>
World top two Wang Nan and Li Ju, Zhang Yining, Sun Jin, Li Nan
and Cheng Hongxia emerged victorious.
</P>
<P>
The other quarter-final spots went to South Korean Rye Ji Hae and
German Jing Tian-Zorner. 
</P>
