<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IATA: Air Travel Safe for Passengers Despite Y2K Bug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Travel by air is safe for
passengers despite the millennium computer bug (Y2K), said the
International Air Transport Association (IATA) here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
However, the passengers should be patient of certain
inconveniences like flight delays or a long wait for their
baggage, caused by the Y2K problem, the IATA said.
</P>
<P>
"It's not a question of safety. It's not a question of planes
falling out of the sky," said Nancy Gautier, communications
manager at the IATA's Year 2000 (Y2K) Project.
</P>
<P>
"Safety is the first priority of the air transport industry,
and this will not be compromised on any day of the year, including
during the millennium changeover period," said the IATA in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
It said that the Y2K bug might cause luggage to go astray,
impair baggage carousels or delay flights, but it would not
endanger passenger safety.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K bug stems from the fact that many computer systems in
use today will encounter difficulties in processing the date
changeover from 1999 to 2000 unless they undergo costly and
time-consuming modification.
</P>
<P>
Experts fear that many computers worldwide could malfunction or
crash on January 1, 2000. Many older computers allocate only two
digits to represent the year. Thus, 2000 may be read as 1900.
</P>
<P>
According to an IATA survey, airlines have spent more than 2.3
billion U.S. dollars to ensure their computer systems were immune
from any problems arising from the year 2000 changeover and the
results of worldwide air transport tests for year 2000 compliance
were encouraging so far.
</P>
<P>
"We can say that in every continent the work is very solid.
Some continents are almost at an advantage because their equipment
isn't highly computerized to begin with," said the IATA official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-05 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
