<HEADLINE> Russia Boycotts "Peace Shield-99" Maneuver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Thursday that it
boycotted the "Peace Shield-99" exercises because they are under
the Partnership for Peace program of NATO, at a time when Moscow's
relations with the alliance remain frozen.
</P>
<P>
Russia's ties with NATO have been frozen since the military
bloc launched a 78-day air campaign against Yugoslavia on March
24.
</P>
<P>
The Russian Defense Ministry noted that the United States and
Great Britain, both participants of the bombings on Yugoslavia,
are taking part in the exercise, the Interfax news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The time-frame for the resumption of Russian-NATO military
relations is largely dependent on the cooperation between them in
Kosovo, the only area in which the two parties are cooperating at
present, Defense Ministry officials said.
</P>
<P>
"Peace Shield-99" began Thursday at the Lvov training grounds
of the Ukrainian Western Command, with the participation of over
1,200 servicemen from Ukraine, Azerbaijan, Belgium, Britain,
Bulgaria, Denmark, Georgia, Greece, Latvia, Moldova, Poland,
Romania, Turkey and the United States.
</P>
<P>
Observers from Estonia, Norway, Kazakhstan, Lithuania, France
and Hungary are also participating.
</P>
<P>
The multinational contingent will train in the maintenance of a
cease-fire between parties to an ethnic conflict in two countries,
Interfax said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
