<HEADLINE> Annan Demands Earliest Release of All Hostages in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan Thursday called upon a Sierra Leonean group to release
all detainees, including U.N. military observers, at once and
without any conditions.
</P>
<P>
The appeal, contained in a statement issued here by a U.N.
spokesman, came in the U.N. chief's first response to reports that
former junta soldiers demanding humanitarian aid kidnapped 13 U.N.
military observers, four journalists and a group of West African
peacekeepers in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General deplores this serious incident and urges
the armed group to release all detainees immediately and without
any conditions," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"He also calls on the Government of Sierra Leone and RUF (the
rebel Revolutionary United Front) leader Foday Sankoh, as well as
ECOWAS (the Economic Community of West African States) and its
military group ECOMOG, to do their utmost to seek the earliest
release of all detained personnel and to ensure the safety and
security of all international staff assisting the Sierra Leonean
people to implement the Lome Peace Agreement," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General is deeply concerned at the detention, at
Ocra Hills on August 4, by an armed Sierra Leonean group of United
Nations military observers and civilian personnel, the
Nigerian-led ECOMOG troops who escorted them, as well as local
journalists," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The soldiers abducted their captives Wednesday when the
fighters were supposed to hand over 150 women and children taken
prisoner during the West African country's bloody civil war, which
ended last month after the signing of the Peace Agreement in Lome,
capital of Togo.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place at Ocra Hills, a forested, hilly area
about 65 kilometers east of the coastal capital, Freetown. The
detainees were held by former soldiers of the Armed Force
Revolutionary Council, the junta that seized power in a 1997 coup
and was ousted in 1998 by the West African peacekeepers, known as
ECOMOG, reports said.
</P>
<P>
The Government of Sierra Leone and the junta signed the Peace
Agreement in Lome on July 7 to end the eight-year civil war, in
which tens of thousands of people were killed, and many more were
mained by rebels in a terror campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
