<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Learn From Uganda in Combating AIDS: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Health Department will
continue to fight HIV/AIDS by adopting Uganda's successful model
of mobilizing society against the scourge, Health Minister Manto
Tshabalala-Msimang said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the return of a high-profile delegation from a
four-day fact- finding mission to Uganda on strategies to fight
the epidemic, she said: "Social mobilization is key to prevention
and, before we have a cure, that is where we need to concentrate."
</P>
<P>
"Ugandans are very open about HIV and AIDS. This is what we as
South Africans really have to learn -- the openness is an
essential tool against the stigmatization of the disease."
</P>
<P>
Strategies that encouraged this openness and mobilized
communities were needed in South Africa, she said.
</P>
<P>
"Openness helps Ugandans to give each other support. AIDS has
strengthened the extended family concept and has helped to
destigmatize the disease."
</P>
<P>
Political commitment at the highest level was part of creating
that openness but civil society, churches and traditional leaders
also had a significant role to play, as had been seen in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
She reiterated the necessity for openness about the disease as
an important part of prevention, which is one of the main reasons
the government has cited to back its plan to make AIDS a
notifiable disease.
</P>
<P>
Uganda is the only country in Africa that has reduced its
HIV/AIDS infection rate substantially through an awareness
campaign that begun 10 years ago. About 1.9 million people in
Uganda are HIV-positive out of a population of 20 million.
</P>
<P>
But these successes were not linked to the use of medication,
the minister noted.
</P>
<P>
Referring to tests on Uganda's newly announced retro-viral drug
(which initial findings show reduces transmission from mother to
child during pregnancy), Tshabalala-Msimang said: "There's no
conclusive evidence, but we're testing it. There's also a cost
issue here -- and we don't want to raise the expectations of our
population yet."
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan drug, which is presently being tested in clinical
trials, is considerably cheaper than its counterpart AZT, costing
34 rand (5.6 U.S. dollars) instead of 400 rand (66 dollars) per
treatment.
</P>
<P>
There was also a lesson to be learnt from that country on
integrating culture and tradition in AIDS prevention programs, and
to translate the knowledge of how HIV is transmitted into changed
sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
South Africa would also seek to create the situation now
prevalent in Uganda where the level of awareness focused on
abstinence among the youth, faithfulness to one partner and condom
use.
</P>
<P>
A declaration of intent on cooperation in vaccine research and
training was signed with Ugandan officials during the visit.
</P>
<P>
Other objectives had been to look at home care plans for the
infected, caring with orphans, the impact on the social security
system, how to reach school children through life skills training
and civil sector partnerships.
</P>
<P>
"We came back as a South African delegation absolutely
inspired, absolutely motivated, " said Tshabalala-Msimang.
</P>
<P>
"If Uganda can do it, so can South Africa. We have fought many
battles. We can't be defeated by a virus," she said.
</P>
<P>
About four million people are reportedly infected with the AIDS
virus in South Africa, which has a population of 43 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
