<HEADLINE> S. African Green Party Opposes Passage of Nuclear </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's Green Party
Thursday joined the chorus of opposition to the two nuclear fuel
ships expected to round the Cape in September and urged government
to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Party spokesman Jeremy Acton said in a statement: "It is
unacceptable to accept the passage of this highly dangerous cargo
around South Africa's exclusive economic zone, without the
provision of any protection."
</P>
<P>
The government should negotiate at the highest level with the
governments of France, Britain and Japan, in order to ascertain
the course, position and speed of these vessels.
</P>
<P>
The ships, Pacific Teal and Pacific Pintail were bound for
Japan via Britain and France.
</P>
<P>
The two vessels, transporting recycled nuclear fuel for
Japanese power stations originate from Britain via a French
reprocessing plant.
</P>
<P>
They left France on July 16 amid protests by Greenpeace, a non-
governmental eco-conservationist group.
</P>
<P>
"According to international accords on the transport of nuclear
material of this nature, a naval escort should be provided, but
this has been ignored and the shipping nations wish to
irresponsibly shirk the duty of guarding this shipment," Acton
said.
</P>
<P>
The South African Green Party also urged government to send the
navy to escort these vessels once their positions have been
divulged to security forces.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Environmental Affairs Valli Moosa has also
expressed concern over the shipment and Deputy Minister Joyce
Mabudafhasi met British, French and Japanese diplomats for a
briefing on the shipment.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said that Cabinet had already decided in
1997 that vessels carrying nuclear material around the South
African coast should be treated strictly in accordance with
national and international law.
</P>
<P>
She said the government's overriding interest was to minimize
risk to human health, marine life and the environment by ensuring
the safe passage of the ships to Japan.
</P>
<P>
She had been given assurances at the briefing that the ships
would not dock at any South African harbor.
</P>
<P>
"Further assurances were received that the radiological
protection and safety arrangements meet international standards,"
she said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
