<HEADLINE> Masood Says Ready for Talks With Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Anti-Taliban leader Ahmad Shah
Masood Thursday said that war is no solution to Afghanistan's
problems and he is ready for talks with the ruling Taliban
militia, the Afghan Islamic Press (AIP) reported from Kabul.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Pakistan-based agency from the front
lines north of Kabul, Masood said: "After regaining the positions
we lost early this week, we are now ready for talks with the
Taliban to rule out differences."
</P>
<P>
He claimed that his forces killed more than 400 opponents,
including Pakistani and Arab militants, during the counter
offensive early Thursday morning, in which they recaptured several
strategic towns including Charikar, the provincial capital of
Parwan.
</P>
<P>
"War is not in the interest of the Afghans, it only serves the
interests of our enemies," the AIP quoted Masood as saying.
</P>
<P>
Masood, a former Afghan defense minister, is known as the Lion
of Panjsher for his gallantry against Soviet troops in the
mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
He is regarded as the only formidable obstacle left to the
Taliban militia's ambition of extending their rule over the whole
Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
