<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets End Sharply Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON August 5 (Xinhua) - US inflation fear and weaker than
expected US productivity figures pulled European markets down on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 lost another 133.8 points to close down 2.14
percent at 6101.6 after hitting 6079 earlier in the day. It was
London's lowest close in almost four months.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300, a broader index of the largest pan
European shares, reflected the nervous mood as it fell 2.3 percent
to 1235.41.
</P>
<P>
The big faller was Anglo-Dutch publisher Reed International
which was down 41.25p at 424p after revealing a big fall in
profits and announcing a major review of its operations.
</P>
<P>
Telecom shares continued to be hit hard by profit-taking
following broker comment on excessive valuations. They were
responsible for 23 points of the day's total fall.
</P>
<P>
The Xetra Dax in Frankfurt fell further in afternoon trading
after a morning session depressed by disappointing numbers from
two key sector members.
</P>
<P>
The index ended the session down 140.92 points at 4978.45, a
loss of 2.75 percent, having earlier hit a low of 4948.
</P>
<P>
Some traders blamed the fall on general concern that US shares
were about to take a dive. Others said the strength of the euro
had helped to trigger the downward momentum.
</P>
<P>
Paris was also feeling the pressure from Wall Street. The
CAC-40 index closed 85.50 points lower at 4240.70. It had fallen
to 4221.00, its lowest level since 1 April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
