<HEADLINE> Sudanese Government Declares Cease-Fire in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Sudanese government has
declared a two- month comprehensive cease-fire in its war with
southern rebels in consideration of human suffering in the war
zones, sources available here said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources, the Sudanese Ministry of Foreign
Relations Thursday issued a statement in capital Khartoum,
declaring a cease-fire in the southern areas of the country and
calling on the rebel group to act the same.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire would start at midnight Thursday and end on
October 5, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the government was concerned about the suffering
of the people in the conflict-stricken regions and the cease-fire
would enable them to receive relief aid.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the rebel Sudan People's Liberation Army (SPLA)
declared a three-month cease-fire in Bahr al-Ghazal, Western and
Central Upper Nile regions in southern Sudan.
</P>
<P>
However, the government regarded the SPLA's action merely as
propaganda and urged the rebels to declare a comprehensive
cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
In mid-June, the Sudanese government and rebels met in Kenyan
capital Nairobi for the five-day fourth round of Sudan peace talks
and made no substantive progress on major controversial issues.
</P>
<P>
Both sides at the talks agreed to set up a permanent
secretariat in Nairobi to facilitate peace negotiations and
accepted a special envoy, a Kenyan senior diplomat, to conduct
shuttle diplomacy between them.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese civil war has ravaged the southern part of
Africa's largest country. Over 1.5 million people have died
during war and famine since 1983 when the fighting restarted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
