<HEADLINE> UNEP Urges Attention for Indigenous People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Environment
Program (UNEP) Thursday urged the international community and
national governments to assess indigenous people's needs and
accelerate the correction of situations that put them at
disadvantage.
</P>
<P>
"Out of 6,000 languages that are spoken today, 2,500 are in
danger of extinction," UNEP Executive Director Klaus Toepfer said
in Nairobi in a message to mark the International Day of the
World's Indigenous People, which falls on August 9.
</P>
<P>
The pace of extinction is accelerating both for cultures of the
 indigenous people and for biological species, he noted.
</P>
<P>
As global socio-economic factors disrupt traditional ways of
life, the knowledge of their environment is being rapidly lost,
causing poverty and over exploitation of the environment by both
local groups and outside forces, Toepfer said.
</P>
<P>
"External pressures also promote tensions and conflicts over
indigenous peoples' land rights and impinge on their human rights
-- including linguistic, cultural and resource rights," he added.
</P>
<P>
With the completion of the fifth year of the International
Decade of the World's Indigenous People, it is an opportunity to
bring about tangible improvements in the daily life of indigenous
people, Toepfer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
