<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Releases Russia's Secrets on Kennedy's Assassination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States Thursday
released about 40 top secret documents held by the Soviet Union
about the assassination of former U.S. President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
The documents show that Kennedy's wife, Jacqueline Kennedy,
wrote to Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev nine days after her
husband's assassination, saying the U.S. policy of "restraint"
would continue.
</P>
<P>
The 80-over-page documents, including the application of
alleged Kennedy assassin U.S. national Lee Harvey Oswald for
Soviet citizenship, were in a package file which was sent by
Russian President Boris Yeltsin to U.S. President Bill Clinton as
a gift in June.
</P>
<P>
However, Jacqueline's letter was translated from Russian into
English. The original copy of the letter is not released.
</P>
<P>
"You and he were adversaries, but you were also allies in your
determination not to let the world be blown up," Mrs. Kennedy
wrote to Khrushchev on December 1, 1963.
</P>
<P>
"I know that President (Lyndon) Johnson will continue the
policy my husband believed in so deeply -- the policy of
self-control and restraint -- and he will need your help."
</P>
<P>
"The danger troubling my husband was that war could be started
not so much by major figures as by minor ones," the letter said.
</P>
<P>
"If only in the future major figures could still force minor
ones to sit down at the negotiating table before they begin to
fight!"
</P>
<P>
The documents were released by the U.S. National Archives after
they were translated into English from the original Russian
version.
</P>
<P>
The document also contains materials about obtained by the
Soviet officials and diplomats about Oswald. In it was a copy of
Oswald's letter in October 1959 to the Supreme Soviet in which he
asked to be made a Soviet citizen.
</P>
<P>
"I want citizenship because I am a communist and a worker, I
have lived in a decadent capitalist society where the workers are
slaves," Oswald wrote in the letter.
</P>
<P>
"I do not have enough money left to live indefinitely here, or
to return to any other country."
</P>
<P>
The documents show the process how Oswald was allowed to stay
in the Soviet Union and married a Soviet citizen but was never
granted citizenship.
</P>
<P>
"Because no decision had been reached on Oswald's request by
the time his visa expired and he was to leave the USSR, Oswald
tried to commit suicide by slitting a vein," one document said.
</P>
<P>
On November 22, 1963, Oswald was arrested in Dallas in the
United States when Kennedy was assassinated. He was shot to death
by Dallas nightclub owner Jack Ruby two days after the
assassination.
</P>
<P>
Some documents about decisions and policies of the Soviet Union
towards the United States after Kennedy's assassination were also
released.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Apartheid S. Africa's Chief Assassin Granted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The South African apartheid
regime's chief assassin, Eugene de Kock, was Thursday granted
amnesty by the Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) for the
1988 bombing of Khotso House, the headquarters of the South
African Council of Churches.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the former commander of the Vlakplaas
police unit, which used murder and torture to defend white rule,
has been pardoned for any of his crimes for which he is serving
several life sentences.
</P>
<P>
Former law and order minister Adriaan Vlok, former police chief
Johann van der Merwe and 14 other policemen were also pardoned by
the TRC's amnesty committee for their role in the 1988 bombing.
</P>
<P>
The committee said in its judgment that amnesty had been
granted to all the applicants in respect of public violence and
malicious damage to property, and the unlawful possession of arms,
ammunition and explosives for bombing Khotso House.
</P>
<P>
Evidence was led before the committee that Vlok discussed the
plan to bomb the building with Van der Merwe, who was then head of
the Security Police.
</P>
<P>
They submitted a report to then State President P.W. Botha and
the matter was discussed by the now defunct State Security
Council. The committee said Botha instructed Vlok to look into
the matter in depth and take the necessary steps to make the
building unusable.
</P>
<P>
Botha has categorically denied his role in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
In his reaction, African National Congress spokesman Smuts
Ngonyama said his party hoped the amnesty decision had been well
considered, "with the aim of taking our country forwards with
respect to reconciliation."
</P>
<P>
The ANC would have to study the judgment before arriving at a
more informed view.
</P>
<P>
"Generally, we respect the position of the amnesty committee,
but we still have to study the formal judgment," he said.
</P>
<P>
Former South African Council of Churches president, Frank
Chikane said Thursday that he respected the TRC decision.
</P>
<P>
He said in a statement that he could never condone the bombing
of Khotso House but was willing to accept the TRC's judgment in
the interest of reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
"The bombing of Khotso House, was an abominable action in
defense of a crime against humanity, and a heresy.
</P>
<P>
"The act of the bombing, like the system of apartheid itself,
cannot be justified and will always be repugnant."
</P>
<P>
Chikane said he had been part of the efforts to set up the TRC
to bring about peace and reconciliation in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
"In this context, I respect and abide by the decision of the
TRC amnesty committee... in the hope that such a deed will never
again be committed."
</P>
<P>
Chikane said several discussions were held with the then
National Party (NP) government after the bombing, and the NP had
always denied the involvement of state security forces.
</P>
<P>
"Yet there was never any doubt as to who the perpetrators of
the dastardly deed were," said Chikane, who is now
director-general in the president's office. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
