<HEADLINE> Foreign Countries Write off $371M of Tanzania's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign countries have
cancelled more than 371 million U.S. dollars of external debts
owed by Tanzania in recent years, Deputy Finance Minister
Abdisalaam Issa Khatibu said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the repayment of 584.482 million dollars of debts
has been rescheduled, Khatibu told the National Assembly
(parliament) in the central city of Dodoma.
</P>
<P>
Khatibu said that the debts were written off following
agreements between the Tanzanian government and governments of
France, Germany, Austria, Norway, the Netherlands, Canada, the
United States, Belgium, Britain and Brazil at the Paris Club
Donors Conference held in Paris in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The deputy finance minister was answering questions raised by
MP Richard Ndassa of the ruling Revolutionary Party, who wanted to
know among others the amount of debts written off by foreign
countries and the names of the states, reports reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
By June 30 this year, the total external debt committed by the
Tanzanian government reached 7.97 billion dollars, according to
the central Bank of Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Khatibu said the Tanzanian government has been
taking loans and grants for social services such as roads,
education, health, agriculture, finance, harbors and tourism
sectors. 
</P>
