<HEADLINE> Nigerian Senate President Rejects Allegations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The president of Nigeria's
109-member Senate, Evan Enwerem, Thursday branded allegations
against him as "wicked fabrication and calculated attempt" to
tarnish his image.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Abuja, the third in the
hierarchy in the west African nation dismissed the letter
purportedly signed by the Chief Secretary to the Premier of the
defunct eastern Nigeria describing him as a convict as "a
forgery".
</P>
<P>
"A competent court of jurisdiction dismissed the letter as
worthless in 1992 after my election as Governor of Imo State," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The document, on which the weekly "Tell" story accusing the
senate president was based, was formerly dismissed as worthless by
a elections tribunal, Enwerem told the press conference.
</P>
<P>
He again denied allegations against him that he had a twin
brother with the same name of Evan.
</P>
<P>
"I never claimed I had a twin brother who is late and whose
name is Evans," he added. Describing the allegations as "recycled
by certain persons whose aim is to use the public media to damage
my name, integrity and office", the Senate president called for
caution in the publication of such material.
</P>
<P>
Enwerem said he was fully in favor of exposing "the
inadequacies of public office holders," but the press should be
wary of being "employed by blackmailers for the prosecution of
private malice."
</P>
<P>
The senate president expressed this after the country's House
of Representatives asked him Thursday to step aside, for an
unimpeded probe of allegations forwarded by the Lagos-based "Tell"
weekly.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian Senate also directed its committees on ethics and
privileges; national security and intelligence; judiciary, human
rights and legal matters to investigate and ascertain the truth of
the matter and submit their findings to the House within 48 hours.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
