<HEADLINE> U.S. Argues for Revenge Violence on Serbs in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States argued on
Thursday that it was reasonable that ethnic Albanians take violent
revenge against Serbs but unreasonable to expect NATO to protect
all Serbs.
</P>
<P>
"It shouldn't be a surprise to anyone... Albanian people of
Kosovo -- when the Albanians were freed from these shackles, that
there would be the potential for revenge and retaliation against
Serbs," State Department spokesman James Rubin told a regular
briefing.
</P>
<P>
"And it is simply not possible for NATO to be in a position to
ensure that all the Serbs stay, or that every Serb is free from
violence," he said.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the U.S. has no evidence that the anti-Serb
violence is an organized policy of the KLA, the Kosovo Liberation
Army, which has been sought independence of Kosovo through
violence.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's very important for people to understand that NATO
never could, nor can the U.N., guarantee that people stay in
Kosovo," Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
The Human Rights Watch based in New York said in a recent
report that more than 100,000 Serbs have fled Kosovo since NATO
troops went into Kosovo. The ethnic Albanians began ethnic
cleansing against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
Criticizing the double standard of the West, some critics say
this shows a failure of the policy to build a multi-ethnic Kosovo
and the peacekeeping mission in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
In the name of protecting humanity and human rights, the
U.S.-led NATO conducted a 78-day air bombing against Yugoslavia
before their troops went in Kosovo. 
</P>
