<HEADLINE> U.S. Life Expectancy Reaches 76.5 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The life expectancy of the
United States was 76.5 years in 1997, up from 76.1 in the previous
year as death rates from HIV, heart disease, cancer, stroke and
homicide declined, according to statistics released Thursday by
the federal Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDCP).
</P>
<P>
White women had the highest life expectancy at 79.9 years,
followed by black women (74.7), white men (74.3), and black men
(67.2).
</P>
<P>
The gap between whites and blacks was down from 6.6 years in
1996 to 6 in 1997. Between men and women, the gap narrowed from 6
years to 5.8 during the same period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
