<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Praises U.S. Economy But Warns of Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The performance of the U.S.
economy during the past years had been remarkable, but there were
significant risks facing the economy, the International Monetary
Fund (IMF) said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In an annual review of the U.S. economy, the IMF said that
transitory factors have helped fuel the recent rapid growth of
demand and cautioned that any abrupt reversal of these factors
could cause problems for macroeconomic management.
</P>
<P>
"Executive directors commended the authorities for their sound
fiscal and monetary policies, which together with the remarkable
flexibility of the labor and product markets, had helped produce
what is now approaching the longest economic expansion in U.S.
history," the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
"In the period ahead, however, directors considered that the
growth of demand would need to slow to a rate more in line with
the economy's long-run productive potential," the IMF stressed.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said one of the biggest risks facing the U.S. economy
is the danger of a substantial and abrupt decline in U.S. equity
prices.
</P>
<P>
"Directors noted that the strength of demand...had been
underpinned by the high level of stock prices -- a level that was
difficult to explain -- and they were concerned that a sharp
market decline could have significant effects on both domestic and
foreign economies," the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
The IMF said the sharp widening of the external current account
deficit and the appreciation of the dollar had been important
factors in allowing rapid domestic demand growth without
rekindling inflation, but cautioned that they could not be
permanent.
</P>
<P>
The IMF also cautioned that although strong investment and
continued productivity gains had probably raised potential output
more rapidly than in preceding periods, "the economy still face
resource constraints, and the recent very strong growth in
domestic demand could not be sustained for much longer without
having inflationary consequences."
</P>
<P>
In these circumstances, the IMF said that, unless there was
evidence soon that the strength of demand growth was abating, the
authorities should tighten monetary policy further to ensure that
the expansion remained on a sustainable noninflationary path.
</P>
<P>
"The policy challenge for both the United States and its
international partners would be to restore a more sustainable
pattern of demand growth in a nondisruptive manner," the IMF said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Rise Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks rose sharply
Thursday as bargain-hunting investors stepped into a downward
market.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 119.05 at 10,793.82.
Until Wednesday, the blue chip stocks fell 535.07 points or 4.77
percent from the record closing high of 11,209.84 set on July 16.
</P>
<P>
The market tumbled in early trading after the Labor Department
reported that American workers' productivity slowed significantly
while labor costs surged in the second quarter. The report pushed
the Dow index down as much as 108 points.
</P>
<P>
But the market recovered when investors stepped in for
bargain-hunting.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index rose 8.38 at 1,313.71 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq index rose 25.83 at 2,565.83, leaving it 10.5 percent below
the record closing high of 2,864.48 set on July 16.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE composite index rose 2.93 at 617.39 and the Russell
2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.05 at 429.75. But the
American Stock Exchange index fell 0.86 at 776.09.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers on the News Stock
Exchange with 1,817 down, 1,196 up and 514 unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 854.21 million shares from 781.25
million in the previous session. 
</P>
</TEXT>
