<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S'pore Revises Visitor Arrival Growth Forecast Upward </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Singapore Tourism Board
(STB) said Friday that it has revised upward its forecast growth
in visitor arrivals for 1999 from 1-3 percent to 6-8 percent.
</P>
<P>
STB said in a press release that a hefty nine percent surge in
foreign visitor arrivals in the first half of 1999 has prompted it
to revise its total visitor arrivals significantly upward.
</P>
<P>
STB said that visitor numbers reached 3.3 million by the end of
June this year, rising nine percent year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
This means Singapore can expect between 6.6 and 6.7 million
visitors for the whole year of 1999 and register a six to eight
increase compared to last year, STB said.
</P>
<P>
The figure is much higher than the forecast growth of one to
three percent made at the start of the year, it added.
</P>
<P>
STB had forecast an increase of between 1 to 3 percent above
the total of 6.2 million arrivals in 1998 when 13.3 percent fewer
visitors arrived in Singapore than the previous year and each
traveler spent 712 Singapore dollars (424 U.S. dollars) per visit.
</P>
<P>
The board said an upturn in visitor arrivals from major markets
like Australia, China, India, Indonesia, South Korea, Thailand and
Britain contributed to the upward revision and it attributed the
upturn to sustained economic recovery and its intensive marketing
efforts.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the upward revision of its tourism arrival
figures comes as STB's latest survey shows that visitors are also
arriving in bigger groups and spending more during their stay in
Singapore. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
