<HEADLINE> Two Dead, Six Missing in Bering Strait Storm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A storm that hit the Chukotka
coast of the Bering Strait Wednesday has left two people dead and
six others missing, the Interfax news agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sixty residents of the Chukotsk Autonomous District were
returning in four whaling ships and five motor boats from St.
Lawrence Island of the United States when the storm began.
</P>
<P>
They were celebrating their ethnic holiday with members of the
U.S. Innuit community in the island.
</P>
<P>
Several people fell into the stormy water. Two of the five
people who were picked up died of exposure. Two motor boats with
six people on board remain missing.
</P>
<P>
An American woman journalist who traveled to Bukhta
Provideniya in Russia to cover the life of Russian Innuits was
among the survivors, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Search and rescue operation, hampered earlier by bad weather,
will resume once the weather improves. Russian border guard
helicopters and army planes will take part in the operation. The
U.S. Coast Guard in Alaska is also prepared to join the search.
</P>
</TEXT>
