<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Unemployment Rate Holds at 4.3 Percent in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. unemployment rate
remained steady in July at 4.3 percent, matching the June number
and near a three-decade low, the Labor Department reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Department said that employers added 310,000 jobs to their
payrolls. The strength in hiring last month reflected big gains in
demand for workers at temporary help agencies, which posted their
strongest rise in 18 months. Hiring of workers also showed big
gains at restaurants, computer companies and engineering firms.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing managed to post a gain of 31,000 workers in July,
after adjusting for seasonal variations, only the second increase
in 16 months.
</P>
<P>
July's 310,000 gain in payroll jobs far exceeded many analysts'
expectations. It followed an increase in June of 273,000.
</P>
<P>
The July increase in payrolls was well above the monthly
average of the first six months of the year of 208,000.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report Friday, the Labor Department also reported
that average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures,
jumped by 3.8 percent in July compared to a year ago, the second
straight month that price pressures have risen. The 3.8 percent
increase compared to 3.7 percent in June and was the biggest gain
since a 4 percent rise in January.
</P>
<P>
Friday's report was the third report in a week showing an
acceleration in wage pressures. On Thursday, the government said
that unit labor costs rose at the fastest pace since the end of
1997. And, last week the government said that the Employment Cost
Index climbed at its most rapid pace in eight years.
</P>
<P>
Given the tighter labor markets, many economists expect Fed
policy-makers would make another quarter-point increase in the
federal funds rate when they meet on Aug.24.
</P>
<P>
Most of strength in July came from gains in service industries
led by the jump of 61,000 jobs at restaurants and bars, almost
double the gain in June. Employment was also up at car
dealerships, hardware and garden supply stores.
</P>
<P>
Construction added 22,000 jobs in July, but mining lost 3,000
jobs as the oil and gas industry continued to suffer layoffs. This
industry has lost one-fifth of its jobs, a total of 71,000
layoffs, since February of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0080 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meets on U.N. Presence in Congo (K) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
Friday met in an open session to discuss a July 16 report by U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who asked the 15-nation body to
approve 90 military observers immediately to serve as liaison
officers to the main belligerents in the 11-month conflict in
Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
The Security Council agreed informally after its consultations
some two weeks ago to send the 90 military observers to Congo (K)
in preparation for a possible peacekeeping mission in the central
African country, but has delayed a resolution until the United
States agrees, diplomats here said.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council is expected to vote a draft resolution on
the U.N. presence in the African country, U.N. sources said.
</P>
<P>
"Members of the Security Council have finalized their
consultations on a draft resolution that authorizes the deployment
of up to 90 military liaison personnel," the Council president for
the month of July, Agam Hasmy of Malyasia, told reporters after a
closed-door meeting on July 23.
</P>
<P>
The resolution under consideration said the observers are to
provide information in planning operations "for a possible further
role of the United Nations" in implementing a peace agreement once
all parties have signed it.
</P>
<P>
Annan, in his July 16 written report to the Security Council,
asked the Council to immediately send the 90 military observers as
liaison officers to the main warring parties in the conflict,
which broke out in August last year in eastern Congo (K), also
known as the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations hopes for thousands of international troops
and 500 military observers to help maintain a cease-fire in the
vast central African nation once all warring parties agree to put
down their guns.
</P>
<P>
Six African countries involved in the war in the former Zaire
singed a cease-fire agreement on July 10 in Lusaka, capital of
Zambia. The signatories included the rebels' supporters Rwanda and
Uganda as well as President Laurent Kabila of Congo (K), who was
backed by troops from Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia. 
</P>
