<HEADLINE> Stepashin Urges Support for Russian Manufacturers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Sergei
Stepashin said his government will try to support domestic
manufacturers and protect the home market in the face of a flood
of foreign imports.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Vechernyaya Kazan newspaper,
Stepashin said protecting Russia's food manufacturers is
particularly important as "the pressure of imported products is
particularly heavy" in the country's food market.
</P>
<P>
"Imports of food suppress our... agriculture, which has for
centuries brought fame to the country, drive us into foreign
dependence and, as a consequence, undermine the economic security
of Russia," Stepashin said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Russia's financial crisis of August of last
year had given more chances to Russian manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
"The devaluation of the ruble has somewhat increased the
competitiveness of import-replacing industrial products," he said.
The official exchange rate of the national currency is 25.5 rubles
to one U.S. dollar, against the pre-crisis rate of about 6.3
rubles to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
"In the first few months after the August crisis, industry in
11 regions of Russia not only did not reduced its pace but
actually grew by several percent," Stepashin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
