<HEADLINE> South Korea's Warships Make First Port Call to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Two destroyers of the South Korean
Navy made a port call to the western Japanese port of Sasebo on
Friday after concluding a joint naval exercise with Japan's
Maritime Self-Defense Force (MSDF) on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
King Kwanggaeto, a 3,855-ton destroyer loaded with helicopters,
and Chung Nam, a 2,180-ton destroyer, became the first South
Korean navy warships to visit Japan.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Navy officers will visit the Sasebo city office
and meet with Japanese counterparts to brief them on the drill.
The two military vessels are scheduled to depart on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The two destroyers, together with three warships from Japan's
MSDF, participated in the search-and-rescue drills conducted in
the East China Sea Between Japan's westernmost main island of
Kyushu and the Cheju Island, south of the Korean Peninsula.
</P>
<P>
The drill, in which the five ships trained for responding to
fires on civilian vessels, marked the two countries' first joint
military exercise.
</P>
<P>
The drill drew strong criticism from the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea (DPRK), which described the maneuver on Thursday
as a prelude to a new Japanese invasion. 
</P>
