<HEADLINE> Malawi's Fund-lack Family Planning Body to Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BLANTYRE, Malawi, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The National Family
Planning Welfare Council of Malawi will close at the end of this
month due to lack of funding, leaving about 85 percent of its
staff out of work, Malawi News Agency reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The government announced last year it would stop funding 21
statutory corporations including the Copyright Society of Malawi,
Medical Council of Malawi, Malawi College of Accountancy, and
Nurses and Midwives Council of Malawi, the agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Executive Directors Martin Palamuleni said in a telephone
interview that the family planning council will close down because
government, which used to give the council eight million kwacha
(about 320,000 U.S. dollar) annual subvention has stopped funding
it until about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Established under an act of parliament in 1990 to advocate,
coordinate and support family planning and other reproductive
health activities, the council has about 40 members of staff.
</P>
<P>
Health Secretary Wesley Sangala said in a separate interview
that activities of the council will now be handled by ministry's
reproductive health and population services units.
</P>
<P>
He said the government could not afford the council because it
required a lot of money, much of which came from donors.
</P>
<P>
Government consulted the donors before arriving at the
decision, Sangala explained, adding that government has prepared
an end-of-service package for the council's staff.
</P>
<P>
Sangala hoped that some members of staff would get similar jobs
with the Kenyan Organization International Parenthood Association
to be launched in the country next month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
