<HEADLINE> AIDS Transmitters May Be Convicted in Malawi </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Malawian people with HIV/AIDS
involved in conduct likely to spread the disease, might soon face
criminal charges when the law commission completes a review of
the penal code on infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
The country's daily Nation newspaper Quoted commission member
on criminal justice, Rosemary Kanyuka, as saying that the public
will be consulted before making a proposal on whether to make the
deliberate spread of HIV/ AIDS a criminal offence.
</P>
<P>
"The commission will be conducting workshops to seek public
opinion starting from the end of this month to see how best the
issue of criminalizing AIDS can be tackled." said Kanyuka at a
public lecture by the visiting U.S. judge Lajune Thomas Lange in
Blantyre Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Commission's law reform officer Matilda Katpopla said Thursday
the move to treat people who deliberately spread HIV/AIDS as
criminals is in line with the review of the penal code under the
provision that deals with infectious diseases, the Malawi News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
She said the commission had already made progress by
recommending that courts give stiffer sentences to people who
commit sexual offences.
</P>
<P>
"The commission has also planned to conduct study tours within
the SADC (South African Development Community) region so that we
can learn about how other countries deals with such cases," said
Katopola. 
</P>
</TEXT>
