<HEADLINE> Kenya Launches Laws on Water Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Water is one the major components
targeted for priority action by the Kenyan government under its
National Poverty Eradication Plan, Water Resources Minister Arap
Ngeny said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Launching a sessional paper on national policy on management
and development of water resources, the minister said one of the
major challenges in water sector has been the sustainability of
the 1,800 water schemes spread all over the country.
</P>
<P>
The Kenya News Agency quoted the minister as saying that at
present, about 74 percent and 50 percent of Kenya's urban and
rural population respectively have access to safe drinking water.
</P>
<P>
Due to the lack of appropriate emphasis on the existing water
schemes in the past, the minister said, the government has
adapted various policy options in the water sector.
</P>
<P>
Ngeny pointed out that the sessional paper launched expounds a
policy that encourages more active involvement of the private
sector in the development and management of water resources.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was encouraged by the situation in which a
large number of operators such as self-help groups, organized
communities and non- governmental organizations have been
attracted to start operating water projects.
</P>
<P>
The document has further laid more emphasis on sewerage
development, institutional framework and financing the water
sector, the minister added.
</P>
