<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France, Greece Face Legal Action for Tax Rule Offenses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
decided to bring an action before the European Court of Justice
against France for its violation of value-added tax (VAT) rules
while giving a warning to Greece for its discriminatory tax
application in the sector of alcoholic drinks.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission, the EU's executive body, said it made
this decision after the French authorities refused to amend their
legislation to comply with the Community law and made no proper
response to a reasoned opinion sent to them on March 10, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The EU executive body said the French legislation requires that
vehicles, aircraft and boats used for the instruction of drivers
and pilots be assigned exclusively to that purpose if they are to
qualify for VAT deduction.
</P>
<P>
Such a condition of exclusive use is not laid down in a related
EU directive and "therefore restricts the right to deduct, which
is one of the fundamental principles of the VAT system", it said.
</P>
<P>
Under the EU law, the European Commission has the right to
enforce rules in the whole 15-country European Union. It will
first send a letter of formal notice after finding out any
activity in a certain member country involving law violation.
Then it will send a "reasoned opinion" to the country if it did
not receive a satisfactory response.
</P>
<P>
Finally, the EU executive body will make a decision to bring an
action before the court against the country if it did not get a
proper answer from the country in two months.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, the commission is giving a warning to Greece
through a reasoned opinion to force the country to change its
original rule application. It said in a statement that Greece has
applied a reduced tax rate on the alcohol used in the manufacture
of a spirituous drink called ouzo, which is produced exclusively
in that country.
</P>
<P>
The reduced tax rate is half of that imposed on all other
spirituous drinks, including all such drinks produced in other EU
member states, the commission said. "Such a difference clearly
discriminates in favor of the national producers in Greece, which
is where ouzo is exclusively produced," it added.
</P>
<P>
"If the necessary amendment is not made to the Greek tax system
within two months of receipt of the reasoned opinion", the EU
executive body said, it could bring the matter before the European
Court of Justice, the highest EU jurisdictional agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
