<HEADLINE> U.S. Girls Receive Over 100,000 Postcards Against Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 100,000 postcards have
been received since January 1996 when two young girls from the
United States launched their "One Million Postcrd Campaign"
against the sanctions on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to collect one million postcards to President
Clinton," 12-year-old Kouthar Al-Rawi said here Friday at a show
in the Palais des Nations sponsored by the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO).
</P>
<P>
Kouthar and her 10-year-old sister, Marwa, asked adults and
children around the world to draw or write a postcard to U.S.
President Bill Clinton requesting him to lift the sacntions on
Iraq for the sake of the children.
</P>
<P>
"At the end of the bombing against Iraq in January 1991, the
war didn't end for the Iraqi children," said the sisters.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 4,500 innocent Iraqi children die each month, they
said.
</P>
<P>
Kouthar and Marwa Al-Rawi said that the United States
government is virtually alone in its insistence to uphold the
economic sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"President Clinton, the people of Iraq are hungry, they are
thirsty, and the children continue to die," they wrote.
</P>
<P>
