<HEADLINE> Highlights of Diplomatic News Today </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Following are the highlights of
diplomatic news released by Xinhua here today:
</P>
<P>
 Jiang Zemin Calls for Greater U.N. Role
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin said here today that to help
realize the comprehensive economic and social development of
developing countries, the role of the United Nations (U.N.)
organizations should be increased.
</P>
<P>
China is willing to continue conducting and reinforcing
cooperation with the U.N. and its organizations, Jiang said in a
meeting with administrator Mark Brown of the United Nations
Development Program (UNDP) this morning in the summer coastal
resort of Beidaihe.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said that China's cooperation with the UNDP has been
fruitful, and has served as a channel for China in learning
foreign scientific and technological developments, absorbing
advanced technology, and drawing on advanced management experience.
</P>
<P>
Brown said the UNDP highly appreciates the Chinese government's
support for its work, and it is willing to join with the Chinese
government to contribute to the reform, opening and modernization
drive ongoing in the country.
</P>
<P>
 MOFTEC Minister Meets UNDP Administrator
</P>
<P>
China hopes that the United Nations Development Program (UNDP)
will continue to offer technological assistance on a universal,
neutral and gratuitous basis.
</P>
<P>
Shi Guangsheng, minister of foreign trade and economic
cooperation, in a meeting today with UNDP administrator Mark Brown,
said China is satisfied with its cooperation with the UNDP over
the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
Brown said that the UNDP will continue its efforts to help
China's economic growth and social development.
</P>
<P>
 China Regrets Escalating Afghanistan Conflict
</P>
<P>
China expresses its regret for the escalation of the recent
internal conflict in Afghanistan, Chinese Foreign Ministry
Spokesman Zhu Bangzao said here today.
</P>
<P>
He said that China sincerely hopes that the two parties in the
conflict pay much attention to the national and state interest,
cease fire as soon as possible, and seek a proper, peaceful
settlement of the Afghanistan issue through consultations and
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
 China, Japan to Cooperate in Information Technology
</P>
<P>
Representatives of China and Japan signed several agreements on
a five-year term of cooperation in projects concerning information
technology.
</P>
<P>
The agreements cover six pilot projects concerning information
technology to be implemented before March 2003 -- a comprehensive
study of the movement of goods, long-distance education and
medical diagnosis, agricultural production and distribution, flood
monitoring and prevention, and forest fire prevention.
</P>
<P>
The information technology cooperation project is one of 34
projects agreed upon during President Jiang Zemin's visit to Japan
last November. It is also the first governmental cooperation
project between China and a foreign country in the information
technology sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
