<HEADLINE> Writethru: Death Toll Rises to 92 in Philippine Flooding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from the recent
landslides and flash floods that hit the northern Philippines rose
to 92 with the recovery of nine more bodies at the Cherry Hills
subdivision, an official report said Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The National Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) said in a
report that at least 36 people are still missing and 35 others
have been injured.
</P>
<P>
The total number of families affected by the monsoon heavy
rains in Metro Manila and nearby provinces reached 349,121 or
1,708,846 persons while about 129,607 hectares of agricultural
lands have been destroyed worth 333 million pesos (8.3 million
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
According to the NDCC, estimated damage to infrastructure was
placed at 70 million pesos (1.8 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Some 235 evacuation centers have been set up in Metro Manila
and the nearby provinces of La Union, Pangasinan, Tarlac,
Pampanga, Bulacan, Zambales, Nueva Ecija and Rizal sheltering
12,794 families or 58,530 persons.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC said 32 of the fatalities were residents of Cherry
Hills subdivision in Rizal province where landslide destroyed 179
town houses on Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Rescue workers working round-the-clock since Tuesday night are
still looking for the more than 30 missing people.
</P>
<P>
Armed Forces chief General Angelo Reyes said the military which
is spearheading the massive search and rescue effort from the
start will gradually turn over the job to non-government
organizations, the police and other volunteer groups in the next
few days.
</P>
<P>
He said only a small number of military personnel and heavy
equipment operators will remain to assist the rescue workers.
There are about 300 military personnel involved in the rescue
operation.
</P>
<P>
Although four days have passed since the killer landslide
struck Cherry Hills, Reyes is hoping against hope there are still
survivors underneath the rubble.
</P>
<P>
"The reality is that the debris and the soil structure and the
buildings are so unstable that if you hurry up the removal of the
debris, the whole thing might collapse so we have to work very
carefully on this," he said.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC said rescue and clearing operations may take another
week because of the complicated situation on the spot.
</P>
<P>
As time passed, hopes were fading for the more than 30 people
who were believed trapped underneath the tangle of concrete slabs,
twisted iron sheets, and steel, said the NDCC.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-five residents of the subdivision were rescued within a
few hours after the landslide. But none have been recovered alive
since then.
</P>
<P>
The government assured the public Friday that ongoing
investigation of the cause of the tragedy will yield the guilty
parties.
</P>
<P>
"Definitely somebody will have to be held responsible,"
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in a radio interview
Friday morning. But he declined to comment further pending the
results of the investigations.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the Presidential Palace expects to get at least an
initial report by Monday from the investigating committee, which
was tasked Thursday by Philippine President Joseph Estrada to wrap
up its probe in 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
Estrada Thursday inspected the site of the landslide, where he
reiterated the need for the early passage by the Congress of the
Land Use Act which will rationalize further the housing program of
the country.
</P>
<P>
He also formed the investigating team to determine the
liability of parties responsible for the tragedy and vowed to
institute measures to prevent tragic landslides in the country.
</P>
<P>
Another landslide occurred in Caloocan City of Metro Manila on
Thursday night and endangered three houses. Fortunately, the
occupants of the houses managed to get out of their abode into
safety.
</P>
<P>
Weather improved Friday over the northern Philippines after
hammering the region with monsoon rains since Sunday, and
floodwaters have started receding in several provinces.
</P>
<P>
With the receding water level, life is now gradually getting
normal in some flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
The education authorities of Metro Manila also said the classes
in elementary and secondary schools might resume next Monday as
flood waters in several areas of the city have begun to subside.
</P>
<P>
The meteorological authorities said that while rains were
expected in the northern Philippines until Sunday, these would be
confined to early mornings, late afternoons and early evenings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
