<HEADLINE> China, Japan Sign Project Agreements on Information Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Representative of China and Japan
signed several agreements on a five-year term of cooperation in
projects concerning information technology.
</P>
<P>
Chinese officials and businessmen from northeast China's
Liaoning Province, Shenzhen City in south China's Guangdong
Province, Tianjin and Shanghai municipalities, Hubei Province in
central China and the Beijing Union Hospital, among others, signed
the documents along with the Japanese representatives.
</P>
<P>
The agreements cover six pilot projects concerning information
technology to be implemented before March 2003 -- a comprehensive
study of the movement of goods, long-distance education and
medical diagnosis, agricultural production and distribution, flood
monitoring and prevention, and forest fire prevention.
</P>
<P>
China's State Development Planning Commission (SDPC), Japan's
Ministry of International Trade and Industry and companies from
both countries will cooperate in using advanced multi-media
systems for the planned projects, according to SDPC officials.
</P>
<P>
The information technology cooperation project is one of 34
projects agreed upon during President Jiang Zemin's visit to Japan
last November. It is also the first governmental cooperation
project between China and a foreign country in the information
technology sector.
</P>
<P>
The two countries signed a memorandum of understanding on
cooperation in February in Beijing, stating that between April
1998 and March 2003 they would spend from 2.5 billion to 3.0
billion Japanese yen (about 21.15 million US dollars to 25.38
million US dollars) on the pilot projects.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
