<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Find 100 Liver Cancer-Related Genes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Scientists at the Shanghai
Institute of Cell Biology under the Chinese Academy of Sciences
have discovered more than 100 genes which are related to the
incidence of liver cancer in humans.
</P>
<P>
"We used the cDNA array to find those genes," said Dr Hu Gengxi,
head of the institute's Max-Planck Guest Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
The cDNA array is a preliminary stage of bio-chip, which can
provide the most rapid biological analysis by integrating
thousands of items of biological information into a tiny piece of
material, Hu explained.
</P>
<P>
Besides the liver-cancer related genes, they have also found
more than 300 human genes with similar functions since they
started experiments at the end of 1998, said Hu.
</P>
<P>
"We plan to identify 25,000 genes, or one fourth of the total
number of human genes," Hu added.
</P>
<P>
He said that his laboratory is also trying to develop a kind of
bio-chip which can help carry out early-stage diagnosis on cancer
such as liver cancer.
</P>
<P>
Hu said that large-scale cancer checks will become a reality if
a new low-priced bio-chip can be used for diagnosis. It will only
take a few minutes to complete one check by using such a bio-chip,
he explained.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
