<HEADLINE> Myanmar Says Khun Sa Still Under Government's Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Former drug warlord Khun Sa, who
surrendered to the Myanmar government in early 1996, is still
living under the government's care and doing legal business such
as gems mining with his children, said a Myanmar military official
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Colonel Thein Swe, head of the Department of the Office of
Strategic Studies of the Myanmar Defense Ministry, said at a press
conference here that Khun Sa is living in accordance with his
promise that he would never be engaged in drug trafficking again
after his surrender.
</P>
<P>
Thein Swe also disclosed for the first time that Khun Sa had
agreed to three promises for his surrender demanded by the
government: unconditional surrender, keeping away totally from
drug trafficking after the surrender and living under the
government's arrangement to obtain full security provided by the
government.
</P>
<P>
Khun Sa, together with his 15,000-strong Mong Tai Army, laid
down their arms to the government in January 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
