<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Buy 8 Strategic Bombers From Ukraine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia will buy eight strategic
Tupolev-160 bombers from Ukraine before the end of the next month,
Colonel-General Anatoly Kornukov, commander of the Russian air
force, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The planes will be brought to Russia as partial payment for
supplies of natural gas to Ukraine, which owes Moscow around 1
billion U.S. dollars. The deal was struck during Russian Prime
Minister Sergei Stepashin's recent visit to Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
"A decision to this effect has been made and, I think, we will
move these planes to Russia before the end of September," the
Interfax news agency quoted Kornukov as saying.
</P>
<P>
The bombers will significantly increase the capability of the
country's strategic air force group, Kornukov said. The purchase
will bring the total of the group's number of strategic missile
carrying Tu-160s to 15.
</P>
<P>
The group will be stationed in Engels, Saratov region,
Kornukov said. "We have well-trained crews for every plane to be
obtained from Ukraine," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kornukov said 85 percent of Russia's fleet of some 50 Tu-95MS
and six Tu-160 strategic bombers are combat ready with more than
enough crews to fly them. The crews flew an average of 21 hours
last year and 12 hours in the first half of 1999.
</P>
<P>
Tu-160 and Tu-95MS bombers carried out long-range flights
during a major war game earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine owns 19 Tu-160 bombers based in Priluki, Chernigov
region, and 21 Tu-95MS bombers in Uzin, Kiev region. These planes
were meant to carry cruise missiles capable of delivering nuclear
warheads.
</P>
<P>
A delegation of Russian air force officers and Tupolev design
bureau experts have recently visited the Ukrainian bases to find
that only 60 percent of the bombers were fit to fly, The Moscow
Times reported, quoting an official with the Russian air force.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
