<HEADLINE> Swedish Largest Opposition Party Leader Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Secretary-General's
special envoy for the Balkans Carl Bildt resigned on Friday as
leader of Sweden's largest opposition party, the Moderaterna Party.
</P>
<P>
Bildt, 50, told a news conference that he had expressed his
wish of stepping down to his party in April.
</P>
<P>
This is the best time to announce his decision of resignation
because he is determined, according to Bildt.
</P>
<P>
He did not explain the reason for his resignation at the news
conference. Local political analysts said more and more
Moderaterna Party members are complaining that Bildt focused most
of his attention on international politics while ignoring Swedish
domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
The Moderaterna Party will elect a new leader in September.
</P>
<P>
Bildt took the post since 1986 and served as the country's
prime minister from 1991 to 1994.
</P>
<P>
He began focusing his attention on international politics in
1995, when he became the European Union's mediator to the conflict-
torn Bosnia. He won a international reputation for successfully
brokering a peace agreement there.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed as the U.N. envoy for Balkans in May this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
