<HEADLINE> Lukashenko Denies Politics Behind Charges Against Former PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Belarussian President Alexander
Lukashenko said Friday that charges filed against former Prime
Minister Mikhail Chigir, accused of embezzling 10 million U.S.
dollars, have nothing to do with the ex-premier's activities as an
opposition leader.
</P>
<P>
Chigir was arrested last May on suspicion of embezzlement as
head of the Agroprombank commercial bank, a position he held
before becoming prime minister in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Lukashenko, citing the prosecutor general, said Chigir was
accused of stealing 10 million dollars. "Concrete documents prove
this," the Interfax news agency quoted Lukashenko as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said Chigir's arrest "has absolutely nothing to do" with
the fact that he became an opposition activist after being
dismissed as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
"What does politics have to do with this?" Lukashenko said, "
Let those who've stolen money return it, and we'll consider
releasing such people from custody." 
</P>
