<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Foreign Currency Reserves Stand at 89.1 Bln Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Monetary
Authority (HKMA) said on Friday that the official foreign currency
assets of Hong Kong amounted to 89.1 billion U.S. dollars at the
end of July 1999.
</P>
<P>
Including unsettled forward contracts, the foreign currency
assets of Hong Kong at the end of July 1999 also stood at 89.1
billion U.S. dollars, according to an HKMA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
In terms of foreign currency reserves ranking, Hong Kong is the
world's fifth largest holder of foreign currency reserves,
following Japan, China's mainland, Taiwan and Germany, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The increase of 500 million U.S. dollars in settled foreign
currency assets during the month reflects mainly the valuation
effect of foreign currency investments held by the Exchange Fund,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, the total foreign currency assets
of 89.1 billion U.S. dollars represent over seven times the
currency in circulation, one of the highest ratios in the world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Contest Promotes Public Awareness of Elderly Needs in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The contest aims to pay tribute to the elderly for their
contributions to society and their families, both in the past and
at present, encourage the elderly to play an active role in
community affairs and enjoy a well-earned "golden age," and
promote understanding among people of different generations in a
move towards a society for all ages.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the HKEC's Central Co-ordinating Committee for
International Year of Older Persons (IYOP) 1999, it is of a scale
unmatched so far, said Hui Yin-fat, chairman of the Program Sub-
Committee.
</P>
<P>
Hui urged all eligible elderly people to support the contest
which gives recognition and helps pay tribute to the tremendous
contributions elderly people have made, and will continue to make,
to society.
</P>
<P>
Out of the large number of entries expected in each region, 10
will be selected. The three with the highest scores in each region
will participate in the territory grand final to be held on
December 18, 1999 and to compete for the most coveted honor ever
shown publicly to the older generation.
</P>
<P>
Top winners of the contest will receive valuable prizes
including a gold-plated souvenir plate and an appreciation
certificate. Winners on individual aspects of performance will
each receive a trophy.
</P>
<P>
Tam Yiu-chung, chairman of the IYOP Central Coordinating
Committee, estimated that more than 100,000 elderly people have
participated in a wide range of activities held at district and
territory-wide levels since the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
"Many people have expressed the wish that the efforts put into
enhancing the awareness of the needs of the elderly this year
should continue beyond 1999," said Tam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
