<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Market Booming in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Bond market is booming in
Singapore with corporate debt issuance totaling 9.0 billion
Singapore dollars (5.4 billion U.S. dollars) in the first half of
1999, equal to the amount for the whole of last year.
</P>
<P>
Singapore-dollar issues by statutory boards and foreign
entities ballooned to 4.0 billion Singapore dollars (2.4 billion
U.S. dollars) from practically nothing.
</P>
<P>
The revelation was made by Minister for Health and Second
Minister for Finance Lim Hng Kiang Thursday when he made
congratulatory remarks on the announcement of the first batch of
financial institutions awarded the Approved Bond Intermediary
status.
</P>
<P>
Singapore has carried out a number of reforms in the financial
sector since last year, including liberalizing commercial banking
and upgrading local banks, boosting bond markets and liberalizing
guidelines on the internationalization of the Singapore dollar.
</P>
<P>
Recognizing that a vibrant bond market is important to the
overall development of Singapore's financial sector, the
government has introduced various new policy initiatives to boost
Singapore's debt markets and make the operating environment more
conducive to bond players.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the implementation of these initiatives, the
number of bond issues increased significantly and representation
of issues by both foreign and local entities became much broader.
</P>
<P>
Various efforts have been made in Singapore to boost its debt
market.
</P>
<P>
A committee has been set up by the government to spearhead bond
issuance by the statutory boards and both the public and private
sectors have been encouraged to engage in the bond market for
capital raising.
</P>
<P>
A host of tax incentives have been introduced to promote the
development of an active bond market and foreign entities have
been allowed to issue bonds in Singapore dollar.
</P>
<P>
A key component of the country's strategy to develop the debt
capital market is to attract reputable global fixed income trading
and arranging teams to base their Asian operations in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve the objectives of drawing more
international debt teams into Singapore and tap the Singapore
dollar market, the Monetary Authority of Singapore introduced the
Approved Bond Intermediary or the ABI scheme in this year's
budget.
</P>
<P>
Carrying out this scheme, the MAS announced Thursday the first
batch of 16 financial institutions awarded the Approved Bond
Intermediary status after evaluating their debt origination and
trading capabilities in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
Once a financial institution has been accorded the ABI status,
all debt security lead managed by it will be treated as qualifying
securities. The ABI will also be exempt from tax on fee income
from debt market activities while holders of the qualifying
securities will enjoy a 10-percent concessionary tax rate on
interest income.
</P>
<P>
Singapore aims to play a key role as a leading international
hub in Asia, dealing also in non-Singapore dollar issues.
</P>
<P>
The MAS believes time has come for Singapore companies to
actively engage in the bond market as the environment and
sentiment at the financial market have improved much.
</P>
<P>
The government will form a debt market committee comprising
representatives from the MAS and other relevant government
agencies and this multi-agency committee will drive and coordinate
the overall strategies in developing the Singapore debt markets.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also look at how public and private sector
bond-raising could be further encouraged and review and develop a
regulatory and infrastructural environment that is conducive to
the growth of a vibrant debt market.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Lim said, "what we have done are initial steps.
The challenges ahead are to get liquidity in the market."
</P>
<P>
"The government sets the operating framework and we encourage
as many players as possible, " he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
