<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Regional Bank Files for Liquidation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Namihaya Bank, a Japanese regional
bank, filed for liquidation with the Financial Reconstruction
Commission (FRC) on Friday, giving up its efforts to survive with
the issuance of new shares to boost its capital.
</P>
<P>
Shinji Yoshida, president of the Osaka-based, second-tier
regional bank, told a press conference that the bank made the
decision after finding it difficult to recapitalize itself and
unable to repay depositors.
</P>
<P>
Yoshida said the bank foresaw its debts exceeded assets by
nearly 110 billion yen (about 96 million dollars) at the end of
September.
</P>
<P>
Namihaya Bank, the product of a merger of two regional banks in
Osaka last October, has been tottering under the weight of massive
bad loans for some time.
</P>
<P>
The FRC, a government body authorized to put troubled banks
under temporary state control, is expected to convene an
extraordinary meeting Saturday to recognize Namihaya Bank as
insolvent and decide to send bankruptcy administrators to the bank.
</P>
<P>
Even if the bank is declared bankrupt, it could continue doing
business over the weekend with deposits fully protected.
</P>
<P>
Namihaya Bank would be the sixth Japanese bank declared
bankrupt by the FRC under financial reconstruction legislation
aimed at fixing the bad loan-saddled banking system.
</P>
<P>
It would also become the fourth second-tier regional bank
declared bankrupt, following Tokyo Sowa Bank, Kokumin Bank and
Kofuku Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
