<HEADLINE> Indonesian FM to Go to East Timor to Discuss Ballot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas is scheduled to arrive in Dili, capital of East Timor
Saturday to discuss various issues concerning the autonomy ballot
to be held there on August 30, a U.N. official Friday said.
</P>
<P>
"The foreign minister is to meet with the head of the U.N.
Mission in East Timor (UNAMET), Ian Martin, tomorrow for talks on
security, code of conduct for the ballot campaign, and issues on
the process of the upcoming ballot," Antara News Agency quoted
UNAMET deputy spokesman Yasuhiro Ueki as saying in Dili Friday.
</P>
<P>
Ueki said Alatas will be accompanied by a number of ministers.
</P>
<P>
He also said that until Wednesday, the UNAMET had registered
439,580 people for the ballot, 427,190 of whom signed up in East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
According to an announcement by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, the ballot registration period should end on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The code of conduct for pre-balloting political campaigning in
East Timor is expected to be approved this week and it will
subsequently be announced and published next Monday, Ueki said.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the approval of the code of conduct is slow,
the campaign period has not been determined yet. However, the
campaign period is anticipated to be from August 11 to August 27.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations is organizing a direct ballot in East Timor
to enable the East Timorese to accept or reject a wide-ranging
autonomy offered by the Indonesian government early this year.
</P>
<P>
A rejection of the autonomy proposal will mean independence for
the former Portuguese colony.
</P>
<P>
East Timor was integrated into Indonesia in 1976 in a move
never recognized by the United Nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
