<HEADLINE> U.S. Embassy in Tanzania Marks Bombing Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The United States
ambassador to Tanzania Charles Stith and three children Friday
jointly unveiled a memorial plaque for the victims who lost
their lives in the bomb attack on the U.S. embassy here one year
ago.
</P>
<P>
The plaque, a replica of the plaque dedicated at the Department
of State in Washington D.C. in May 1999, will be on permanent
display in the lobby of the embassy, Stith told 200 people who
came to attend the commemoration of the first anniversary of the
embassy bombing.
</P>
<P>
The plaque contains the dead list of 56 people, although at
least 257 people were killed and over 5,000 injured in
simultaneous car bomb attacks on the U.S. embassies in Kenyan
capital Nairobi and Dar es Salaam on August 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Moslem and Christian communities offered
prayers to the victims and a moment of silence was observed at
the temporary site of the embassy, where the commemoration was
held.
</P>
<P>
Guarded by two U.S. marines, the ambassador shook hands with
relatives of the victims and said those who were killed will be
remembered forever.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador later told a press conference that clearance of
the bombed embassy and the Lebon Road in front of it is still
underway but the job will be completed very soon.
</P>
<P>
So far, Stith said his government has granted 9.3 million U.S.
dollars to the victims. He reiterated that perpetrators of the
heinous crimes will be brought to justice.
</P>
<P>
He said a new, permanent embassy will be built in Dar es Salaam
at a cost of 50 million U.S. dollars, adding that it will be one
of the finest projects of the U.S. Department of State.
</P>
<P>
A ceremony for the ground breaking of the new embassy will be
held Saturday afternoon, Stith said.
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S.-Tanzania ties are still strong despite the
bombing case. Tanzanian President Benjamin Mkapa will visit U.S.
next month to bring closer bilateral relationship, he noted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
