<HEADLINE> Thailand to Gain 19 Mln Dollars From Hosting UNCTAD </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is expected to gain a
windfall of 700-800 million baht (19-21 million U.S. dollars) from
the 10th United Nations Conference on Trade and Development, the
state-run Tourism Authority of Thailand (TAT) said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, the first global conference of the 21 century and
the new millennium, will be held at Queen Sirikit National
Conventional Center in Bangkok from February 12 to 19, 2000, TAT
Governor Seree Wangpaichitr said.
</P>
<P>
About 10,000 visitors, including government officials,
prominent business figures, journalists and representatives of
inter-governmental agencies, are expected to attend the meeting,
which will focus on how to make globalization a more effective
instrument for the development of all countries and the world
population.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, as the host of the quadrennial conference, will then
assume the chairmanship of UNCTAD for the following four years.
