<HEADLINE> Thailand, Malaysia Sign Agreements on Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from Thailand
and Malaysia hailed as a success the Eighth Joint Commission
Meeting between the two countries, which ended here Friday.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day meeting, several agreements were signed on
cooperation in border development, communications and
transportation, trade and investment, agriculture and other areas.
</P>
<P>
Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan stressed at the meeting
the importance of continued efforts to strengthen cooperation and
contact along the Thai-Malaysian border. He said the two countries
have agreed to take measures with a view to facilitating
cross-border activities.
</P>
<P>
Surin said activities, such as the extension of the opening
hours of border checkpoints, the opening of new border checkpoints
and the construction of a bridge across a border river, will
"contribute significantly to enhancing the well-being and
livelihood of the two peoples and bringing them closer together in
shared prosperity."
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar hailed the Joint
Commission as a "viable mechanism to review the progress that has
been made in bilateral relations as well as identify new areas of
cooperation."
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1987, the Thailand-Malaysia Joint Commission aims to
enhance bilateral cooperation in the fields of politics,
economics, trade, investment, tourism, education and science and
technology. 
</P>
