<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shenzhen Striving to Promote High-Tech Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- This special economic zone in
south China's Guangdong Province is promoting the development of
high-tech industry by introducing a range of preferential policies
and clearing away some restrictive measures that hindered the
registration of new high-tech businesses.
</P>
<P>
According to newly published policies, non-residents will be
encouraged to apply to start up new high-tech businesses in
Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Previously, it was mandatory for at least one of the
shareholders in a local business to have permanent residence
registration in Shenzhen if he or she wanted to set up a new high-
tech business.
</P>
<P>
The new policies also stipulate that high-tech achievements can
be evaluated as high as 35 percent of the registered capital for
new high-tech businesses, while the registered capital for such
businesses can be paid in installments over two years.
</P>
<P>
During the implementation of the new policies, overseas
citizens will be allowed to hold such posts as members of the
boards of directors, supervisors or managers of new high-tech
businesses.
</P>
<P>
Overseas investors will also be allowed to ignore the benchmark
of 25 percent of the registered capital for starting up new high-
tech businesses.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Shenzhen will be the venue for China's first
international high-tech fair, which will be held October 5-10 this
year.
</P>
<P>
Some 31 Chinese provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities have announced plans to send delegations to the
fair. A large number foreign high-tech companies, including
multinationals such as Microsoft, IBM, Ericsson and Siemens, have
also applied to attend.
</P>
<P>
Government delegations from a number of countries, including
Canada, Australia, Italy and Finland, will attend the fair, along
with representatives from US laboratories and Canadian
universities. In addition, organizers report that a number of
overseas banking organizations have expressed strong interest in
the event.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
