<HEADLINE> S.Leonean Rebels Release Several Hostages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A branch of Sierra Leone rebels
late Thursday released several hostages they kidnapped Wednesday,
according to information reaching here Friday.
</P>
<P>
The released includes two U.N. officials, one Rueter reporter
and one clergy man.
</P>
<P>
The development is believed to be related to the intensive
negotiations underway between the rebels and Foday Sankoh's
Revolutionary United Front (RUF) and Sierra Leone's government.
</P>
<P>
Christo Johnson who was among the freed Thursday said Friday in
Freetown that all the hostages were well and that their captors
wanted food and medicine among other demands.
</P>
<P>
Johnson with other hostages were seized Wednesday in the Okra
Hills region about 65 km east of the country's capital Freetown by
soldiers loyal to a military junta that supplanted elected
President Tejan Kabbah in 1997.
</P>
<P>
About 30 people including U.N. observers, West Africa Peace
Keeping Force (ECOMOG) officials, journalists, and other personnel
were believed to be taken hostages by the rebels.
</P>
<P>
Leaders of the Revolutionary United Front (RUF), who signed a
peace agreement with the government on July 7, said Thursday that
their leader Foday Sankoh had instructed the captors to release
the hostages.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers are former soldiers of the junta that seized
power in May 1997 and were ousted by the West African Peace
Keeping Force of ECOMOG in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers said they would release the hostages if the
peace agreement signed on July 7 in Lome, Togo, was revised.
</P>
<P>
The rebels said they were not satisfied with conditions
accorded them under the agreement which provides that the rebels
share power with the government of President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
