<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Supports Integrity of Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
MOSCOW, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Russia said Friday that it
wholeheartedly supports the integrity of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia, the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The statement, reiterated by officials with the Russian
Foreign Ministry, came after Yugoslavia's Montenegro republic
passed a draft plan Thursday on name change aimed at loosening its
partnership with Serbia.
</P>
<P>
Moscow regards relations between these two constituent
republics of Yugoslavia as an internal affair of that country, the
news agency quoted the Foreign Ministry officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
"What is important is that these issues should be solved
through political dialogue and within a constitutional framework,"
the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Russia will continue cooperating with Montenegro as part of
Yugoslavia, they said.
</P>
<P>
According to Montenegro Prime Minister Filip Vujanovic, the
plan proposes that the name of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
be changed into the Commonwealth of States of Montenegro and
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
The plan suggests replacing the current federal government
with a "council of ministers" and the current two-chamber Yugoslav
parliament with a single house, said Vujanovic, who is supported
by the West.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for the abolition of the central foreign
ministry and the establishment of two separate foreign ministries
instead.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats in Belgrade said that the plan, which is going to be
presented to the parliament of Montenegro and the government of
Serbia, is a result of the West's isolation policy on Serbia,
which, with Montenegro, formed the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
in April, 1992 after the former Yugoslavia fell apart. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
