<HEADLINE> China Steps up Urban Subway Construction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China is expected to step up the
construction of its urban subway system in a bid to reduce urban
pollution and spur the national economy.
</P>
<P>
The government is ready to approve subway lines in cities
including Chongqing, Qingdao and Shenyang, following the recent
approval of a line in Nanjing in east China's Jiangsu Province,
according to vice construction minister Zhao Baojiang.
</P>
<P>
Addressing today's ceremony marking the delivery of the first
batch of cars for a new section of Beijing's subway system, Zhao
said that developing subway systems is important for controling
the worsening air pollution and alleviating traffic congestion in
urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 90 kilometers of subways have been constructed in
Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, and Guangzhou, while some new lines
are under construction in Shanghai, Guangzhou and Shenzhen.
</P>
<P>
Zhao said construction of more subways will also lend a strong
boost to the national economy since subways are an important part
of the urban infrastructure, and their construction may greatly
stimulate the machinery and electronics industries. 
