<HEADLINE> Beijing Purchases Subway Cars for New Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The first order of 30
domestically produced subway cars were delivered today for trial
operations on a new section of Beijing's subway system, which will
begin on September 28.
</P>
<P>
The cars are the fourth and latest generation of China-made
subway cars, and the most advanced yet. A total of 174 cars will
be needed for the new line.
</P>
<P>
The newly completed 13.5-kilometer-long line, which runs from
Fuxingmen to Bawangfen, has 11 stations along the way, and passes
through Tian'anmen Square. It is also the main underground line
along the city's major thoroughfare, Chang'an Avenue.
</P>
<P>
This project is an addition to Beijing's current 42-kilometer-
long subway lines, and was jointly built by the Beijing City
Construction Co., the Beijing Municipal Construction Engineering
Corporation, and the No.16 Engineering Bureau under the Ministry
of Railways.
</P>
<P>
With a total investment of 7.57 billion yuan (908.4 million U.S.
dollars), the project broke ground in 1992, but failed to meet the
original deadline of 1996 due to a shortage of funds.
</P>
<P>
After going into trial operations on September 28, the new line,
with the carrying capacity of 30,000 passenger per hour, is
expected to greatly relieve traffic jams along Chang'an Avenue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
