<HEADLINE> Uganda Slams Congo Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
condemned the alleged air raid Wednesday carried out by Sudanese
planes in the northwestern part of the the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The bombing, which Kampala said to be at the request of
Congolese President Laurent Kabila, claimed a total of 524 lives
in areas bordering Sudan.
</P>
<P>
Barigye Ba-hoku, press assistant to State Minister of Defense
Steven Kavuma, told Xinhua in a telephone interview Friday morning
that the matter is under investigation.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local newspapers said Kavuma and his counterpart for
regional cooperation Amama Mbabazi condemned the incident, saying
that it is a violation of the Lusaka cease-fire accord.
</P>
<P>
Mbabazi said those who refuse to endorse the agreement are to
blame because this is endangering the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Kampala-based New Vision paper said that by attacking the
northern Congo, Sudan was trying to hit the Ugandans where they
can because they are their enemy and to lock Uganda in the war.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Pierre Bemba, leader of the Congolese Liberation Movement,
a rebel group fighting in the northern Congo and backed by the
Ugandan government, said recently that the bombing was done on
behalf of the Congolese government.
</P>
<P>
The Congolese government Thursday denied any link with the
bombing. Information Minister Didier Mumengi dismissed the claim
and called on Bemba to provide proof of his statement.
</P>
<P>
He said Congolese forces respect the cease-fire agreement and
accused Bemba of making the allegations in a bid to keep the war
going.
</P>
<P>
The Khartoum government has denied any involvement in the
year-old Congolese civil war which also sucked in some other
African countries in the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
