<HEADLINE> Monetary Reform in Angola Urgent: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Angolan Financial Minister Joaquim
David said that a monetary reform is urgent and important for his
inflation-torn country, a newspaper here reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
David was quoted as saying Thursday that the monetary reform
will be based on a change of the national currency reajusted
kwanza, or called "a cut of zeros on bank-note".
</P>
<P>
The minister admitted that the currency system of the reajusted
kwanza, with too many zeros in paper money, has caused
insustainable problems in social life and sometimes even beyond
the capability of computers.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the government should have an alternative for the
reajusted kwanza, David said the fundmental objective of the
currency reform is to stabilize social life and the financial
market in his country.
</P>
<P>
The reajusted kwanza has devaluated fast since the turn of the
year when the civil war broke out, hindering the country's
industry from developing.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan government gave up on June 3 the fixed rate of
exchange, in a bid to curb inflation and strike the illegal
currency exchange market.
</P>
<P>
But the impasse in the battlefield and the deteriorating
economic situation prevented the policy from working. On Friday,
the exchange rate in reajusted kwanza against the U.S. dollar is
1:3,080,000 (one dollar for 3.08 million reajusted kwanza), worth
only a quarter of its value on June 2, when it was officially
priced at 1:710,000 in exchange for the dollar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
