<HEADLINE> Ethiopia to Produce Anti-Malaria Chemicals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia is to produce
anti-malaria chemicals itself within this fiscal year starting
July 8, a report reaching here said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Samuel Halala, general manager of the Adami-Tulu Pesticides
Processing factory, was quoted as saying that his factory is due
to produce three types of anti-malaria chemicals in an effort to
check the spread of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the new products, the pesticides factory, which was
established last year with a capital of 51.3 million birr (6.4
million U.S. dollars), has been manufacturing 10 types of liquid
and dust pesticides to protect crops from pests and animals from
ectoparasites.
</P>
<P>
The home-made anti-malaria chemicals not only help reduce
expenses on importing pesticides, but also enable the people to
get them locally with reasonable price at proxy, Samuel said.
</P>
<P>
According to the manager, the quality of chemicals produced in
his factory fully meet the standards set by the Food and
Agriculture Organization of the United Nations and the World
Health Organization.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he said, their efficacy has been proved successful
in the laboratories of Ethiopian agricultural research institutes.
 
</P>
