<HEADLINE> China's Nonferrous Metal Sector Forms New Groups </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua)-- Three nonferrous metal groups,
originally separate entities under the China Nonferrous Metal
Industry Corporation (CNIC), announced their establishment here
today.
</P>
<P>
The three groups are the China Aluminum Corporation (Chalco),
the China Copper Lead Zinc Corporation (CCLZ), and the China Rare
Metals and Rare Earth (Group) Corporation (CRRC).
</P>
<P>
Vice-Premier Wu Bangguo said at the founding ceremony that the
establishment of the three corporations is an important decision
made by the State Council in full consideration of the challenges
and the overall situation of the industry.
</P>
<P>
"This reform symbolizes that China's metallurgical industry is
entering a new stage of reform and development," he said.
</P>
<P>
The vice-premier said that the reform will help the industry
redirect capital, resolve the problem of redundant construction,
and increase its competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
The three groups are now shareholding companies directly under
the government's supervision.
</P>
<P>
Chalco has total registered capital of 15 billion yuan (1.8
billion US dollars) and an work force of 200,000; CCLZ is China's
largest producer of copper, nickel, lead, zinc, and copper, with
capital of 66.5 billion yuan; and CRRC has a total of 48
subsidiaries nationwide. 
</P>
