<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water-Saving Irrigation Brings Good Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China has saved 15 billion cubic
meters of water and increased its grain production capacity by 23
billion kilograms since it began promoting water-saving irrigation
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
By the end of last year, China had spent 25 billion yuan to
build water-saving irrigation facilities covering 5.63 million
hectares of farmland.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, irrigation techniques for 8.66 million
hectares of farmland have been improved, according to sources from
Ministry of Water Resources (MWR).
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China began to develop water-saving irrigation systems
in 300 counties, which marked the beginning of a full-scale
nationwide campaign to promote water-saving irrigation.
</P>
<P>
To date, more than 100 counties have reached state standards,
and over 100 counties have completed most of the construction work,
in addition to the completion of 209 high-yield grain pilot zones
irrigated by water-saving facilities.
</P>
<P>
Preparations are now underway for a water-saving irrigation
project to be created with a 100 million U.S. dollars loan from
the World Bank.
</P>
<P>
An MWR official said that with the financial support of the
central government, 15 provinces, municipalities, and autonomous
regions have been developing rainwater collecting and drip
irrigation projects, helping to bring many farmers in China's arid
and semi-arid regions out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
According to preliminary statistics, during 1997 and 1998,
nearly 400,000 rain-collecting sites and 3.77 million water
cellars, wells, and other types of water-storing facilities were
built in these regions, with a total investment 2.6 billion yuan,
increasing water supplies by 680 million cubic meters annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0166 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
