<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Truth of Falun Gong's Besieging of Chongqing Paper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The besieging of a newspaper in
this southwest China city last November by the Falun Gong cult was
a plotted act aimed at disrupting social stability.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 Falun Gong practitioners besieged and attacked on
the Chongqing Evening News from November 4 to 6 last year after
the local paper reported on the cult and the harm it had done.
</P>
<P>
On November 1, 1998, the newspaper received a hotline call from
a worker at the Southwest Medicine Factory about the break-up of
his family.
</P>
<P>
The next day, the paper carried a story titled "When would
Laughter Return to My Home?" telling the story of the changes in
the worker's wife, Zhang Longhui, who had practiced Falun Gong for
several months and was seeking a divorce.
</P>
<P>
On November 3, Gu Zhiyi, chief of Falun Gong's general
instruction station in Chongqing, gathered a horde of Falun Gong
practitioners and decided to "preach" and demand apologies the
next day at the paper's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
Early on November 4, the paper was surrounded by Falun Gong
practitioners who put up a big banner and forced their way into
the offices of editors and reporters, demanding that the paper
publish an open apology.
</P>
<P>
They also threatened that if the paper did not apologize, they
would exercise their "gong" to "inundate the paper with floods"
and "make the Earth explode ahead of schedule."
</P>
<P>
Editors and reporters at the paper, and its parent paper the
Chongqing Daily, had to stop work and persuade the practitioners
to go home.
</P>
<P>
The Falun Gong practitioners continued their harassment of the
paper for the next two days, and seriously disrupted the normal
working routine there.
</P>
<P>
Now, more and more people involved in Falun Gong have realized
the political nature of the cult, and have broken away from it in
large numbers.
</P>
<P>
Several key Falun Gong members in cities including Beijing and
Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu Province, are reported to
have stood up and exposed the harm done by the cult. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Initiates Program for Preventing Birth Deficiency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Commission Vice Minister Yang Kuifu said at the project's start-
up ceremony that the government's population and family planning
policy includes population control, improving population quality,
and providing natal health care.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China has set a target for population and
family planning for the first decade of the next century: to
maintain the total population within 1.3 billion by 2000, and
reduce birth deficiencies; to maintain the total population within
1.4 billion by 2010; and to provide basic natal health care for
couples of fertility age.
</P>
<P>
Among China's 20 million newborn babies every year, 4 to 6
percent are congenitally deficient, including both visible and
invisible natal deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
Professor Li Zhu of Beijing Medical University said that the
first step for improving population quality is to reduce the birth-
deficiency rate.
</P>
<P>
The State Family Planning Commission has decided to develop
this program for preventing birth deficiencies by establishing a
scientific supervision and prevention system to fulfill the
country's family planning policy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 87 in Philippine Landslides, Floods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from landslides and
floods caused by continuous rains in the northern Philippines in
the past days rose to 87 as of Friday afternoon, the National
Disaster Coordinating Council (NDCC) said in a report.
</P>
<P>
The NDCC also said at least 36 people were still missing and 35
others were injured.
</P>
<P>
In the Cherry Hill sub-division of Rizal province where a
landslide destroyed 179 town houses on Tuesday evening, rescuers
found three more bodies on Friday, bringing the death toll to 30.
</P>
<P>
Rescue and retrieval operations were continued there by teams
from the Armed Forces and the police, assisted by various private
rescue groups.
</P>
<P>
The landslide struck the sub-division in Antipolo City at about
8:00 p.m. on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The government assured the public Friday that the ongoing
investigation of the cause of the tragedy will find the guilty
parties.
</P>
<P>
"Definitely somebody will have to be held responsible,"
Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said in a radio interview
Friday morning. But he declined to comment further pending the
results of the investigations.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said the Presidential Palace expects to get at least an
initial report by Monday from the investigating committee, which
was tasked Thursday by President Joseph Estrada to wrap up its
probe in 72 hours.
</P>
<P>
Estrada inspected Thursday the site of the landslide, where he
reiterated the need for an early passage by the Congress of the
Land Use Act which will rationalize further the housing program of
the country.
</P>
<P>
He also formed the investigating team to determine the
liability of parties responsible for the tragedy and vowed to
institute measures to prevent tragic landslides in the country.
</P>
<P>
Another landslide occurred in Caloocan City of Metro Manila on
Thursday night and endangered three houses. Fortunately, the
occupants of the houses managed to get out of their abode into
safety.
</P>
<P>
The landslides and floods caused by continuous heavy rains in
the past few days affected more than 1.5 million people in the
capital region and nearby provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Department estimated that floods have damaged
nearly 100 million pesos (2.5 million U.S. dollars) worth of rice
and other crops in 10 provinces in the northern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
The meteorological authorities said that while rains were
expected in this area until Sunday, they would be confined to
early mornings, late afternoons and early evenings.
</P>
<P>
Life is now getting normal in some flooded areas as floods are
receding with the easing of the monsoon rains.
</P>
<P>
The education authorities of Metro Manila also said the classes
in elementary and secondary schools will resume at the latest on
Monday as flood waters in several areas in the city have begun to
subside. 
</P>
</TEXT>
