<HEADLINE> Fight Against Smuggling Boosts Import Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, August 6 (Xinhua)-- The tough fight against smuggling
has been boosting the collection of import duties at the port of
Fangcheng in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region since
the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
Fangcheng Customs collected 60.03 million yuan in tariffs
during the first half of this year, a surge of 99 percent over the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Since January 5, when China for the first time ever bombed and
sunk two yachts engaged in smuggling, Fangcheng Customs has
cracked down on 71 smuggling cases involving as much as 5.31
million yuan. These cases mainly involved illegal trafficking in
cigarettes, rubber, and diesel oil 
</P>
</TEXT>
