<HEADLINE> 2 HK Women Voted Most Powerful by Top U.S. Industry Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Two leading tourist women have
been recognized by a major U.S. travel industry magazine for their
work in reviving Hong Kong's profile as a top tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
Amy Chan, executive director of the Hong Kong Tourist
Association (HKTA), and Lily Shum, HKTA regional director for the
Americans, were voted as being among "the most powerful women" in
travel industry in the July 29 issue of Travel Agent magazine.
</P>
<P>
The magazine is a weekly publication for travel agents and
industry personnel involved in both domestic and international
business with a circulation of 53,503 copies.
</P>
<P>
Chan was noted for her ability to lead the HKTA in maintaining
market share in the challenging long-haul North American and
European regions through the "City of Life" campaign and a series
of deals with Cathay Pacific, and for forging stronger ties with
the China National Tourism Administration, boosting Hong Kong's
status as the key entry point.
</P>
<P>
The article also mentions Shum's work in promoting Hong Kong in
North America.
</P>
<P>
"The HKTA has indeed seen a revitalization of interest in the
American marketplace since the middle of 1998," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
She said that she was very honored to be considered one of the
most powerful women in the sector, particularly in the U.S. where
it is at its most competitive.
</P>
<P>
The travel industry in Hong Kong gained momentum in the first
six months this years with a total 5 million arrivals from all
over the world, an increase of 10 percent compared with the same
period of the previous year.
</P>
<P>
"Of the long-haul markets, The Americas remains stable,
registering 516,291 arrivals for the period of the first half of
1999. We aim to maintain growth by actively tapping into new
market segments and developing stronger relationships with the
media and trade," Chan said.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong travel industry brought a robust revenue totaling 55
billion HK dollars (about 7.06 billion U.S. dollars) in 1998,
remaining the pillar industry in the regional economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
