<HEADLINE> PNA Calls for U.S. Intervention Over Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
asked U.S. intervention for a fair and precise implementation of
the Wye Accord, PNA chief negotiator Saed Erekat has said.
</P>
<P>
Several contacts were made with U.S. Special Envoy to the
Middle East Denis Ross and other officials and "we asked their
help so as to ensure honest and timely implementation of the Wye
Agreement because U.S. is a key sponsor of the peace process,"
Erekat was quoted by the Arabic daily Al-Ayam published Friday.
</P>
<P>
The contacts came after the recent conclusive talks between the
Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
During the talks, Israel proposed to postpone the troops
withdrawal from another 13.1 percent of the West Bank stipulated in
the Wye Accord and combine the third of the three-phase pullback
with the final status talks.
</P>
<P>
The status talks, which should have started by May 1996, will
deal with the thorniest issues in the Palestinian-Israeli peace
negotiations, such as the fate of Jerusalem, refugees and borders.
</P>
<P>
Israelis regard the holy city as their undivided and eternal
capital while the Palestinians want it their capital for their
future state.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have pinned hopes on Israeli newly elected
Prime Minister Ehud Barak to implement the Wye Accord that was
suspended by his predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu in early December.
</P>
<P>
The recent inconclusive talks have disappointed the
Palestinians and they rejected any modification to the Wye Accord.
</P>
<P>
PNA Culture and Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo has said
"now we see no need for more meetings."
</P>
<P>
"The meetings are not the problem since they seem to be of no
use. The real problem is that Barak, like Netanyahu, wants to
convey to the world from those meetings as if here is no
trouble. That is nothing but deception," said the minister, who is
also a member of Higher Commission for Negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
