<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Govt Revenue Up in First 6 Months in Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's government revenues
 increased by nearly 50 percent in the first six months of this
year, according to a Ministry of Finance report.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed the increase mainly to the introduction
of the 10 percent value-added tax (VAT) that came into force at
the beginning of the year.
</P>
<P>
VAT alone accounted for 44.2 million U.S. dollars in revenue,
more than 60 percent of the total revenue collected by the
government, the Cambodia Daily reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report also predicts the country will have a 4 percent
growth in its gross domestic product this year.
</P>
<P>
Donor countries have demanded that the Cambodian government
broaden its tax base and carry out extensive fiscal reforms. The
report shows that efforts being made to this end have yielded some
positive results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
