<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Israeli Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Israeli newspapers on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Jerusalem Post:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak spoke with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak by phone on Thursday and briefed him on
development in the Israeli-Palestinian negotiations. Barak's
office said that he assured Mubarak he plans to fulfill all his
obligations under the Wye Accord.
</P>
<P>
Haaretz:
</P>
<P>
-- A personal envoy of Barak met in the past days with
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat in an effort
to establish a private channel of contact between the two leaders
and resolve the dispute over Barak's proposal to modify the Wye
Accord.
</P>
<P>
The envoy is Brigadier General Yitzhak Segev, a former military
governor of the Gaza Strip and an attache of Israeli army in Iran
during the period of the Shah's rule.
</P>
<P>
Yediot Aharonot:
</P>
<P>
-- The Israel Electric Corporation surrendered Thursday to
political pressure from the religious Shas Party, postponing
plans to transport a giant turbine on Shabbat. Shas had
threatened to abstain from voting for the expansion of the
government if the turbine was moved on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Ma'ariv:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Knesset (parliament) Thursday overwhelmingly
approved the addition of five new ministers to Barak's
government. The vote was 52 to 16, and the Arab parties
abstained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
