<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian, Ghanaian Police Probe Arms Smuggling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The International Police (INTERPOL)
of Nigeria and Ghana have begun investigating the case of six
Ghanaians arrested in Lagos for smuggling arms into Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
Ghanaian High Commissioner to Nigeria James Kwofie said
Thursday that the INTERPOL had been asked to unveil the
circumstances surrounding the arms smuggling, according to a New
Nigerian report Friday.
</P>
<P>
Kwofie who is leading a high-powered delegation from Ghana
noted that investigations were going on and it would be premature
at this stage to interfere in the investigations, so the INTERPOL
of the two countries would be comparing notes.
</P>
<P>
He stated that his home government viewed arms smuggling
seriously, especially with the importance his government attaching
to the numerous bilateral relations with Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The action the Ghanaian government would take on the arms
smugglers would to a large extent depend on the outcome of
investigation by the INTERPOL of both countries, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Western Marine Command of Nigeria's Customs Service
intercepted last week in Lagos six Ghanaians in a canoe containing
72,500 rounds of live ammunition and 99 sacks of short gun from
Ghana. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
