<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda, South Africa Sign AIDS Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Uganda and South Africa have
signed an agreement aimed at strengthening cooperation in fighting
HIV/AIDS.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Ugandan Health Minister Crispus
Kiyonga and his South African counterpart Tshabalala Msimang here
Wednesday, Radio Uganda reported Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
This agreement is seeking to boost cooperation on the
development of HIV vaccines, prevention of mother-to-child HIV
transmission, drug research, procurement and distribution as well
as HIV surveillance, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Other areas of cooperation include regulation of traditional
medicine- men, promotion of public and private mix in health care
delivery, and training of experts.
</P>
<P>
South Africa had good drug production, control and distribution
 facilities from which Uganda would benefit, the Ugandan minister
was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tshabalala, who led a 23-person delegation to Uganda, hailed
Uganda's political commitment and social mobilization against the
pandemic.
</P>
<P>
The anti-HIV drug prices could be reduced if the two countries
made joint purchases, she said.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has made remarkable achievement in HIV/AIDS prevention
and control. The prevalence rate of the epidemic in urban areas
has dropped from over 30 percent to the present level of more than
10 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
