<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 08:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Promises to Release Two Detained Turkish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Ambassador to Turkey
Seyed Mohammad Hossain Lavasani has promised that Iran will soon
release two Turkish soldiers, who allegedly entered Iranian
territory.
</P>
<P>
Lavasani made the promise when he had a secret meeting with
Turkish Interior Minister Sadettin Tantan here on Thursday, local
Hurriyet (Freedom) daily reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Lavasani said that the pair will be probably released before
the Turkey-Iran Higher Council on Security meets that is slated
for next Monday in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that Iran's release of the two soldiers will
show a "sign of goodwill" to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Ties between Iran and Turkey were strained when Iran claimed
that Turkish fighter jets hit an Iranian military post and tents
belonging to Iranian tribesmen on July 18.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the bombardment had killed five people
and injured 10 others in the Iranian territory.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has said that the attack was aimed at the outlawed
Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), which uses bases in northern Iraq
for hit-and-run attacks on Turkish territory.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has complained that Iran allowed the PKK to move into
Iranian territory after Turkey threatened to use military force to
oust PKK rebels from Syrian territory last fall. But Iran has
denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Turkish and Iranian officials would
discuss why Iran had reportedly allowed the PKK militants to move
into the Iranian territory during the Monday meeting in Ankara.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been waging a separatist war for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey since 1984. Conflicts between
the Turkish security forces and the PKK rebels have claimed over
37,000 lives. 
</P>
</TEXT>
