<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports People Urged to Stand At Forefront Against Falun Gong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China's top sports administrator
has called on everyone in sports circles to "bravely stand at the
forefront" of the struggle against the Falun Gong cult.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the press here on Thursday, Wu Shaozu,
director of the State General Administration of Sport, said that
Falun Gong has spread malicious fallacies that are "reactionary"
and anti-government.
</P>
<P>
Wu listed several reasons for his call to action. First, Falun
Gong cheated a large number of people who hoped to stay healthy.
</P>
<P>
"We'll never allow Falun Gong to tarnish the good nature of
sports and its glorious tasks, and let the cult continue
bamboozling the masses," Wu said.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, Facts demonstrate that Falun Gong has taken the lives
of many practitioners, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, Falun Gong has never been accepted by sports
administrative departments. It is anti-science theoretically, and
has promoted social unrest politically, Wu said.
</P>
<P>
"Every sports person should take a clear-cut stand in the fight
against Falun Gong," the administrator stressed.
</P>
<P>
In criticizing and exposing the true face of Falun Gong and its
founder Li Hongzhi, "we should enhance our understandings, uphold
materialism and atheism, and strengthen the right ideals and
faiths," he noted.
</P>
<P>
As to those sports people who have been involved in Falun Gong,
Wu said that his administration is taking various steps to help
them break away from the cult and its preaching.
</P>
<P>
Wu stressed that the current campaign against Falun Gong is a
serious political struggle. "We'll make every efforts to make
materialism and atheism prevail in the sports field," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ho Chi Minh City's Industrial Output Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Ho Chi Minh City's industrial
output reached 25,837 billion Vietnamese dong (1.86 billion U.S.
dollars) in the first seven months of the year, up by 8.9 percent
over the same period last year, Vietnam's English daily Vietnam
News reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The city's combined exports in the first seven months amounted
to 2,474 million U.S. dollars, up 14.5 percent compared with the
same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Goods worth 2,008 million U.S. dollars were imported in the
first seven months, a drop of 1 percent compared with the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The city's production, which met with difficulties during the
regional financial crisis, has showed signs of recovery. Increases
in exports were recorded in leather products, frozen shrimp,
garments and footwear. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
