<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Sends Secret Envoy to Meet Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A personal envoy of Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak has met with Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat in an effort to establish
a private channel of contact between the two leaders, local daily
Haaretz reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the meeting was arranged in the past few
days, which was also aimed at resolving the dispute over Barak's
proposal to modify the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
The envoy is reserve Brigadier General Yitzhak Segev, a former
military governor of the Gaza Strip and an attache of Israeli army
in Iran during the period of the Shah's rule.
</P>
<P>
Segev is now a businessman who represents a variety of foreign
companies in Israel and heads an organization called the "Children
of Abraham," which seeks to promote an Israeli-Palestinian peace.
</P>
<P>
Segev maintains ties with a number of figures in the PNA,
including Hani al-Hassan, who is in charge of foreign relations in
the Fatah movement, and the al-Mattar family in Gaza, some of
whose members are close to Arafat.
</P>
<P>
The position of "personal envoy to Arafat" was forged during
Yitzhak Rabin's Labor government. Rabin asked Yossi Ginossar, a
former deputy chief of Israeli General Security Service, to set up
a personal channel between him and Arafat, parallel to the formal
delegations that were holding talks with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
Former prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu's personal envoy to
Arafat was attorney Yitzhak Molcho.
</P>
<P>
The daily quoted a spokesman for Barak's office as saying
that "There are direct contacts between Israel and the PNA."
Barak has proposed to postpone the implementation of the Wye
accord, but the Palestinians insisted that the Wye accord be
implemented verbatim.
</P>
<P>
Diplomatic sources in Jerusalem told the daily that a
compromise will ultimately be found and Arafat will agree to
the proposed delay in the implementation of the Wye agreement
in return for a series of Israeli "gestures" such as the
release of prisoners and economic benefits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
