<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Send More Workers Abroad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam is expected to have an
estimated 25,000 workers employed abroad this year thanks to a
positive influence on the country's labor export industry by the
regional economic recovery, press reports Friday quoted Vietnam's
labor authority as saying.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam's Department for the Management of Overseas Workers
(DMOW) said about 8,000 workers were sent to work overseas in the
first half of this year, with traditional markets such as south
Korea, Japan and Libya receiving the greatest numbers.
</P>
<P>
DMOW predicted that the number of export workers is expected to
increase steadily in the near future.
</P>
<P>
There are 71 labor export agencies operating throughout
Vietnam, according to DMOW statistics.
</P>
<P>
Since 1997, south Korea and Japan have limited the number of
Vietnamese workers due to economic problems in both countries. Now
the two countries' economy is recovering, and it is expected that
more foreign workers will be needed.
</P>
<P>
To fulfill this year's target to export 20,000-25,000 workers,
Vietnam's Ministry of Labor, War Invalids and Social Affairs has
ordered labor export agencies to try to develop the existing
markets in Japan, Laos and Libya, while seeking new markets in
Africa, the Middle East, Europe and Latin America. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
