<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee's Remarks Threaten Taiwan's Future: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan leader Lee Teng-hui's "two
states" remark is in defiance of both Chinese history and the
present situation of cross-straits economic relations, and poses a
threat to the island's future, a senior Chinese economist said
here recently.
</P>
<P>
"Lee is sacrificing Taiwan's future interests to fulfill his
political ambition of separating the island from China," said Hong
Yinxing, a professor of economics and vice president of Nanjing
University in the capital of east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Hong's university has established steady cooperative ties with
several institutions of higher learning in Taiwan over the past
decade, and they have frequently exchanged visits by presidents
and teachers.
</P>
<P>
Hong met many Taiwan business people and scholars when visiting
the island in 1994.
</P>
<P>
"All Taiwanese I've met expect to develop cross-straits
relations and reunify the motherland," Hong said, stressing that
Lee's separatist remarks are against the will of most Taiwanese.
</P>
<P>
Hong indicated that Taiwan has always been an inalienable part
of China in history, and that the Republic of China was replaced
by the People's Republic of China in 1949, which means the former
no longer exists.
</P>
<P>
Hong also pointed out that Taiwan's development is dependent on
the support of the mainland because the island has limited natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
Over the past years, Hong said, Taiwan has transferred its
traditional manufacture of clothing, shoes, and toys to the
mainland, making room for the development of modern industries
such as information technology, which have greatly accelerated the
Taiwan economy.
</P>
<P>
"The Taiwan economy could not have been upgraded if it weren't
for the support of the mainland," Hong added.
</P>
<P>
Hong said that Lee's intention to create two Chinas is
detrimental to Taiwan's economy and is absolutely unacceptable to
Chinese people on both sides of the straits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
