<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's State Sector Enjoys Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China's state-owned assets
amounted to 8.22 trillion yuan ( 993 billion U.S. dollars) at the
end of 1998, surging 13.8 percent year-on-year, according to the
Ministry of Finance.
</P>
<P>
Latest figures from the ministry show that total assets of
state enterprises have grown by 8.3 percent to 13.5 trillion yuan
(1.6 trillion U.S. dollars) although the number of state
enterprises decreased by 24,000 over the past year.
</P>
<P>
Among 238,000 state enterprises, the 9,357 largest registered
an asset value of 7.6 trillion yuan ( 918 billion U.S. dollars) to
account for 56.4 percent of the total assets of state enterprises,
up 9.8 percent on an annual basis.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China has continued its efforts on
diversifying the investment of state enterprises, and state-owned
holding enterprises have grown to account for 10.1 percent of all
state enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The country has also devoted itself to strengthening the role
of state enterprises in key industries in a bid to remove a major
obstacle to national economic growth.
</P>
<P>
While China stepped up restructuring its state enterprises, the
money-losing enterprises were left further behind profit-making
ones, and discrepancies between state-owned and state-owned
holding enterprises have become greater.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
