<HEADLINE> Syrian Paper Voices Pessimism over Peace Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAMASCUS, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hopes for peace progress that
are pinned on Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak began dimming in
view of his retractions and diversions, Syria's leading daily
Al Thawra said Friday.
</P>
<P>
In a commentary, the official paper said after nearly two
months in office, Barak voiced sheer slogans instead of actions
concerning peace while the Israeli hardline attitude remained
unchanged since Barak's predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu's reign.
</P>
<P>
Rescuing the Mideast peace process from the current deadlock
needs a return to the bases of peace, implementing relevant
U.N. resolutions and the land-for-peace principle, the commentary
said.
</P>
<P>
It also said Washington's inactivity to get the peace process
back on track prompted Israel to further delay in enforcing signed
peace accords and work against peace references.
</P>
<P>
Washington's recent decision to give Israel more military aid
has encouraged Barak to skip his campaign promises to move forward
peace and hold more NOs than Netanyahu, said the commentary.
</P>
<P>
Syria's stance is stable and clear to help achieve lasting,
just and permanent peace based on Israel's full pullback from the
occupied Arab territories and implementing relevant
U.N. resolutions and the land-for-peace principle, the commentary
added.
</P>
<P>
The Middle East peace process on the Palestinian, Syrian and
Lebanese tracks have been deadlocked under Netanyahu's
administration. Labor Party leader Barak's winning over Netanyahu
in May election rekindled hope of concerned parties to reactivate
the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
