<HEADLINE> Cyprus to Get Short-range Missiles from Greece </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus is to receive six TOR-M1
short-range missile systems from Greece as part of the exchange
for the long-range Russian S-300 missiles now deployed in Greece's
Crete island, local media reported on Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus' National Guard will receive the first batch of the 21
missile systems once Greece gets them from Moscow.
</P>
<P>
However, Cypriot army's top officials are reportedly concerned
about the island's air defense because the short-range missiles
such as the TOR-M1 and the Italian-made Aspides cannot reach
Turkish airspace for preemptive strikes.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into Turkish Cypriots-controlled north
and Greek Cypriots-dominated south since 1974 when Turkish troops
invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in the wake
of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus had planned to buy S-300 missiles from Russia to cement
its air defense capability.
</P>
<P>
But following intense international pressure and war threats
from Turkey, Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides had to decide to
divert the surface-to-air missiles to Greece's Crete island last
December.
</P>
<P>
Since then, the Cypriot government has struggled to find
alternatives as part of its air-defense umbrella.
</P>
<P>
But there are fears that missiles that could hit the Turkish
mainland, some 80 kilometers away, would raise tensions again in
the region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Joint Venture for Container Transportation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, August 6 (Xinhua) -- An agreement was signed between
two Chinese companies and a Singapore firm in the northeast port
city of Dalian on Thursday on establishing a joint venture to
develop the container shipping business.
</P>
<P>
The venture is jointly funded by the Port of Dalian Authority
in northeast China, the Zhonghai Group based in Shanghai, and the
Port of Singapore Authority (PSA) Group.
</P>
<P>
The new enterprise will introduce PSA's advanced management
system and international standards of operation to promote China's
domestic container transportation sector.
</P>
<P>
For the past few years, domestic container transportation has
been developing rapidly in China, handling 600,000 TEUs (Twenty-
Foot Equivalent Units) last year, and is expected to handle 1.5
million TEUs this year, posing new challenges to port development
in all parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
To date, the port of Dalian has opened seven domestic shipping
lines including the Dalian-Huangpu, Dalian-Shanghai, and Dalian-
Ningbo routes.
</P>
<P>
With this new venture, Dalian is expected to handle 70,000 TEUs
of domestic containers this year, and 170,000 TEUs by the year
2005.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, the port handled 29,000 TEUs,
up 867 percent compared to the same period of last year.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai-based Zhonghai Group, with a fleet of 79 ships and
60,000 containers, now has a 70 percent market share of China's
domestic container transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
