<HEADLINE> Zambia Confident of SADC's Trade Protocol </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Zambia is confident that Southern
African Development Community (SADC) member states will ratify the
SADC Trade Protocol in readiness for the Trade Negotiations Forum
billed for South Africa on August 27.
</P>
<P>
The negotiations will then pave way for the tariff reduction.
The latest Business Line of the chamber of Commerce and Industry
noted that "two thirds of the original 11 signatories have to
ratify the document before the process of implementation can
start."
</P>
<P>
Friday's Zambia Daily Mail newspaper quoted the chamber as
saying that so far, only Botswana, Tanzania, Zimbabwe, Namibia and
Mauritius have ratified the Trade Protocol, out of the
organization's 14 members.
</P>
<P>
A government source said trade negotiations are expected to
come up with agreed goods that would fall on the three-phase
reduction plan.
</P>
<P>
While some goods would be quickly adopted by member countries,
there were sensitive items which a few countries still want to
protect, the source said.
</P>
<P>
"Apparently, this is the category small exporting countries
want to trade in," the source said, adding that if not properly
discussed, negotiations might put the whole tariff reduction
program in jeopardy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
