<HEADLINE> EU Committed to Further Mideast Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Finnish Foreign Minister Tarja
Halonen Thursday night reiterated the European Union's commitment
to further the widely anticipated Middle East peace process, the
Al Nahar newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
After talks with Lebanese Prime Minister Salim Hoss, Halonen
said her whirlwind trip to Beirut "has been very successful."
</P>
<P>
"We have a window of opportunity in the peace process," she
said, without elaborating.
</P>
<P>
Finland, which took over the half-yearly rotating presidency
of the EU in July, is trying to play a more pivotal role in
reviving the peace talks under U.S. auspices.
</P>
<P>
Halonen said the potential for peace has moved to a stage that
will hopefully lead all the way to final negotiations.
</P>
<P>
EU Middle East peace envoy Miguel Angel Moratinos was
accompanying Halonen on the tour which has taken the foreign
minister to Israel, the Palestinian self-rule areas, Jordan and
Syria.
</P>
<P>
Moratinos told reporters that the EU has a "political
commitment" to the regional peace process which is in a "new and
crucial phase."
</P>
<P>
"If we missed this opportunity, it will be a big disaster for
the region," he added.
</P>
<P>
Halonen arrived here from Damascus on Thursday night. She had
held talks with Syrian President Hafez al-Assad on the peace
talks. 
</P>
