<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, August 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA -- The Nicaraguan government is intensifying the
evacuation of around 16,000 people living very near to volcano
Cerro Negro, which erupted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The volcano erupted again at 10 o'clock local time (1600 GMT),
after provoking a large quantity of quakes with top intensity of 4.
7 degrees on the Richter scale, confirmed the Nicaraguan
authorities. (Nicaragua-Evacuate-People)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
SAN JOSE, Costa Rica -- The decades-long internal armed
conflicts in Colombia have displaced about two million people, an
official here told Xinhua Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of this year, almost 800,000 people were
added to the number displaced, head of the International League of
Women for Peace and Liberty (ILWPL), Amparo Elisa Guerrero, said.
</P>
<P>
In addition. there were 180 random killings and 847 political
assassinations in Colombia in the first six months of this year,
she said. (Colombia-Displaced People)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The government of the Republic of Montenegro passed
on Thursday a draft plan on name change aimed at loosening its
partnership with Serbia, reported Yugoslavia's Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
The plan proposes that the name of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia be changed into the Commonwealth of States of
Montenegro and Serbia, Montenegro Prime Minister Filip Vujanovic
told the press. (Yugoslavia-Montenegro)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Hiroshima commemorated the 54th anniversary of the
atomic bombing of this southwestern Japanese city Friday, while
calling for the elimination of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000 people, including atomic bomb survivors, gathered
at the Peace Memorial Park near the center of the bombing, and
prayed for those who died from the world's first atomic bombing in
1945. (Hiroshima-Mark-Atomic Bomb)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- A Northwest Airlines cargo airplane from the United
States was forced to make an emergency landing at Narita Airport
Friday because of a fire in the engine, airport officials said.
</P>
<P>
The jumbo jet landed safely at the airport, which is located
east of Tokyo, at 11:24 a.m. local time (0224 GMT).
</P>
<P>
The fire broke out in one of the engines three minutes after it
took off from the airport at 10:52 a.m. (Japan-Emergency-Landing)
</P>
