<HEADLINE> Share Prices Nose-dive in Tokyo For Third Straight Day </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices plunged in Tokyo for
the third consecutive day Friday as pessimistic sentiment caused
by a strong yen outweighed Wall Street's overnight gains.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 273.95 points, or 1.58
percent from Thursday's close to end at 17,084.24. The key Nikkei
index lost a total of 885.69 points in three days through Friday.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index, covering all First
Section issues, fell 10.34 points or 0.72 percent to 1,420.68.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section went down to 463.35 million
shares from Thursday's 494.23 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Izutsuya Corp. was the day's most heavily traded issue.
</P>
<P>
Traders said weak sentiment which stemmed from the strong yen
in the Tokyo market was not expelled by gains for the first time
in six days on the Nasdaq composite index.
</P>
<P>
Uncertainties over the yen-dollar exchange rate also
discouraged investors to actively buy shares in Tokyo, they said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 825 to 128, with 128 issues remaining unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
