<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Are More Satisfied With Court Results </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- China's courts have been
receiving less criticism this year because the Chinese are more
satisfied with what they are doing, according to a leading judge.
</P>
<P>
Zhu Mingshan, vice president of China's Supreme People's Court,
told a national conference of senior judges here that this year's
campaign to improve the work of courts has helped their image and
has made trials and sentencing fairer.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year, the number of court workers who
had to be sanctioned dropped 36 percent from the same period last
year and the alarming increase in irregularities in recent years
has been checked, Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months, Chinese courts handled 2.72 million
cases, 2.2 million of which were on appeal, an 8.12 and 6.5
percent increase respectively from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
But, in spite of these improvements, there are still problems
in some places, Zhu said, adding that he has asked courts at all
levels to continue improving their work and to make certain that
the rights and interests of all parties are protected.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
