<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwean Bank Raises Minimum Lending Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Standard Chartered Bank of
Zimbabwe has increased its minimum lending rate by five percent to
49.5 percent per annum with effect from Friday, and analysts said
more commercial banks were likely to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
This follows measures introduced by the Reserve Bank last month
to curb high inflationary pressures and discourage the government
and other institutions from borrowing, the daily Herald reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The measures involved the hiking of the bank rate by 2.5
percentage points and the widening of the margin between the repo
rate and Treasury bill rate.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also increased statutory reserves for
commercial and merchant banks by five percentage points to 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank rate would now be maintained at five percentage points
above the effective Treasury bill rate.
</P>
<P>
"Current account rates have been increased by five percent.
Savings and call rates have also been increased. The rate
increases reflect the impact of changes in monetary policy on
market rates, for example Treasury bills," the bank said in a
statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
