<HEADLINE> hke080621 - Medical Staff Drain in New Zealand Keeps Sick Waiting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A shortage of doctors, nurses,
 radiologists, psychiatrists and midwives in New Zealand is
forcing patients to wait long periods for treatment, the Evening
Post reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The shortage has been blamed on large numbers of health workers
shifting overseas, to Australia in particular, higher student
loans, and poor pay and working conditions compared to other
countries.
</P>
<P>
In the capital, according to the Wellington-based newspaper,
there is a 10-month wait for mainly non-urgent CT scans at
Wellington Hospital due to a shortage of radiologists and
technicians.
</P>
<P>
Wellington's staffing problems are echoed in other regions with
 rural areas being the hardest hit.
</P>
<P>
The Evening Post said the New Zealand Health Ministry is aware
of the problem and has organized meetings with different
professions, such as nurses, this month to discuss the issue.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that many hospitals in New Zealand are trying
to recruit from overseas, especially from Britain.
</P>
<P>
It was also reported that more than 300 junior doctors in
Wellington and its nearby district Wairarapa are likely to walk
off the job later this year due to "radical differences of
opinion" in their contract negotiations with hospitals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
