<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scholars Say Society Should Leave No Room for Cults (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Unusual groups or organizations often employ superstitious
means to deify an individual and outsiders know little about this,
so it is quite easy for people with sinister motives to control
and use them for their own purposes, as in the case of Falun Gong,
Jing said.
</P>
<P>
With China's market economy developing and society becoming
more diverse, it is becoming more important for the country to
encourage social groups and organizations grow in a healthy and
regulated way, he said, and the only way the government can
guarantee sound development of organizations and maintain social
stability is to strictly separate normal groups and organizations
from illegal ones and to leave no room for the latter to grow.
</P>
<P>
Jing analyzed the international background of the Falun Gong
and said that as the new millennium approaches, various schools of
thought and cults appear and those with evil motives have already
developed like the 'doomsday' myth and some astrologists are
attempting to predict good or bad lucks. Li Hongzhi and Falun Gong
are just another imitator.
</P>
<P>
Jing said that China needs to increase thought and education
and to promote a scientific world view that is compatible with the
21st century to prepare for a more civilized century. 
</P>
