<HEADLINE> Zambia Won't Record Growth in 1999: Economist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- No economic growth will be
recorded in Zambia this year, Muna Nakalonga, executive director
of the Economics Association of Zambia (EAZ) has said.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on Southern African Development Community (SADC)
executive secretary Preg Ramsamy's announcement that the 14 member
regional group was expecting a three percent growth, Nakalonga
said SADC's growth will not come from Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"Looking at the macro-economic indicators so far registered,
one could see that no growth will be expected this year in
Zambia," Nakalonga was quoted by Friday's newspaper, The Post, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He said Thursday that Zambia's contribution to SADC's projected
regional growth of three percent will only be in the negative.
</P>
<P>
Nakalonga attributed this to the continued depressed economy in
the wake of the soaring inflation levels and low performing mining
sector including the manufacturing sector.
</P>
<P>
Ramsamy announced in a statement Wednesday that SADC projects a
three percent economic growth rate this year after last year's
disappointing 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The projections were based on an improvement in the world and
southern African economic climate.
</P>
<P>
He said free market reforms in the region and initiatives to
attract foreign investment are also likely to boost the growth
rate.
</P>
<P>
"The region has embarked on market oriented economic policies
which gives us hope that there will be some growth," Ramsamy said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, some of the 14 southern African countries in
the grouping had already taken steps to reduce inflation and
budget deficits and stabilize exchange rates.
</P>
<P>
The region needed to achieve at least 6.5 percent economic
growth to make impact on the current high poverty levels which
could be achieved through the fast development of the agro sector,
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
