<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death Toll Rises to 30 in Philippine Landslide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The death toll in the landslide
which destroyed 179 houses at the Cherry Hill subdivision in the
northern Philippines has reached 30 as of Friday morning, the
Philippine News Agency (PNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The rescue and retrieval operations were carried out by teams
from the Armed Forces and the police, assisted by various private
rescue groups, said the PNA.
</P>
<P>
The landslide struck the subdivision in Antipolo City in Rizal
province at about 8:00 p.m. on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The rescue operations began hours after the tragedy, which also
injured 35 people and left 39 more missing as of Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Philippine President Joseph Estrada Thursday inspected the site
of the landslide, where he reiterated the need for the early
passage by the Congress of the Land Use Act which will rationalize
further the housing program of the country.
</P>
<P>
He also formed Thursday an investigating team to determine the
liability of parties responsible for the tragedy and vowed to
institute measures to prevent tragic landslides in the country.
</P>
<P>
According to the PNA, another landslide occurred in Caloocan
City of Metro Manila on Thursday night and endangered three
houses.
</P>
<P>
The death toll from landslides and floods caused by continuous
heavy rains in the past few days claimed more than 70 lives and
affected more than 1.5 million people in the capital region and
nearby provinces.
</P>
<P>
The Agriculture Department estimated that floods have damaged
nearly 100 million pesos (2.5 million U.S. dollars) worth of rice
and other crops in 10 provinces in the northern Philippines.
</P>
</TEXT>
