<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho Accepts Compromise Electoral Model </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Southern African foreign
ministers have persuaded the Lesotho government and opposition to
accept a compromise electoral model for new elections, South
Africa's The Star newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
This emerged at a news conference held in Maseru Thursday night
after two days of difficult talks.
</P>
<P>
South African Foreign Minister Nkosazana Zuma said the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD) and major opposition parties
had agreed on an electoral model which would combine the present
constituency-based "first- past-the-post" system and proportional
representation.
</P>
<P>
Under the "first-past-the-post" model, each constituency has a
seat in parliament and the candidate who receives the most votes
in the constituency gets the seat. Under proportional
representation, the number of seats a party receives in parliament
is in proportion to the percentage of votes it receives in the
election.
</P>
<P>
The "first-past-the-post" system is favored by the ruling LCD,
while opposition parties had insisted on 100 percent proportional
representation model.
</P>
<P>
Zuma said the softening of these positions was the main
achievement of her mission and she was satisfied that enough
goodwill and momentum had been created to reach compromise on this
and other outstanding issues.
</P>
<P>
These include the composition of the Independent Electoral
Commission and the fate of soldiers facing charges for taking part
in the mutiny during the unrest last year.
</P>
<P>
The opposition wants them to receive amnesty while the
government wishes normal justice to take its course.
</P>
<P>
The Southern African Development Community (SADC) mission also
includes foreign ministers from Botswana, Mozambique and Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho held its general elections in May last year, but a
major upheaval followed when the opposition alliance refused to
accept the results and staged massive demonstrations in Maseru.
</P>
<P>
Opposition parties claimed the election was rigged in favor of
the LCD, which won 79 of 80 seats in parliament.
</P>
<P>
South African and Botswana troops, under the auspices of the
SADC, entered Lesotho to quell the unrest.
</P>
<P>
The government and opposition agreed in October to hold fresh
elections within 18 months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
