<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Finds American Students Lack Study Skills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 60 percent of school
guidance counselors believe that American students are not
adequately prepared to tackle homework assignments, said a survey
report released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A national survey conducted by two educational organizations
found that schools in the United States failed to equip their
students with the fundamental study skills to foster increased
academic achievement. In fact, among more than 200 counselors
surveyed, almost 70 percent said that teachers in their schools
think that students have poor study skills.
</P>
<P>
The survey was jointly conducted by the American School
Counselor Association (ASCA), and Sylvan Learning Center which
offers supplemental education programs for students.
</P>
<P>
The results are not surprising as nearly 50 percent of the
schools surveyed do not offer study skills courses to their
students, the report said. Of those that do offer instructions,
only 11 percent require students to take the course and just 10
percent offer it as a separate class rather than incorporating it
into the curriculum.
</P>
<P>
Study skills include organizing and managing time, note taking,
reading and studying, and test-taking strategies such as how to
best tackle multiple choice and essay tests while learning to
conquer test anxiety.
</P>
<P>
"Children are not born knowing how to study," the report said.
"They need to be taught and guided. Sometimes, problems with
homework develop because students haven't acquired the skills to
tackle their studies in an efficient, organized and focused manner.
This creates considerable stress and frustration for families."
</P>
<P>
The survey also found that most guidance counselors think that
it is most effective for students to study together in a group
environment. However, 57 percent of students typically do their
homework at home.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-four percent of the counselors agree that new technology
such as the Internet has greatly changed the nature of homework.
Many students use the Internet a great deal to gather information
for homework assignments. Only 33 percent of schools have a "
homework hotline" for students to call regarding assignments, and
63 percent do not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> American Families Concerned About Growing College Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Americans are more concerned
than ever about their ability to pay for their children's higher
education, according to a report released here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a recent survey conducted by financial organization Merrill
Lynch, 60 percent of respondents say that they are very concerned
about their ability to afford the cost of college education when
their children are ready to attend.
</P>
<P>
According to Merrill Lynch, for the past 20 years, college
costs in the United States have outpaced the general rate of
inflation and, for many families, the expense of college education
is the single largest financial goal.
</P>
<P>
Current estimates predict that when today's newborn child
reaches college enrollment age, the cost of attending a public
institution could easily exceed 80,000 U.S. dollars and more than
200,000 dollars at a private university.
</P>
<P>
The report said that it has worked out a plan providing
Americans with a new, tax-advantaged way to help meet the rising
costs of higher education.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, an individual can set up an automated
investment schedule and contribute 50 dollars a month. When the
beneficiary enters college, account balances can be withdrawn and
used for college expenses.
</P>
<P>
The college-investing plan also permits individuals to
contribute up to 50,000 dollars and a couple up to 100,000 dollars
per beneficiary in a single year without federal gift-tax
consequences, provided no additional gifts are made to the
beneficiary for a five-year period. 
</P>
</TEXT>
