<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Bans Flights to Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The Ugandan government has
suspended commercial flights from Entebbe to rebel-held areas in
eastern part of the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) where some
airlines have been doing brisk business.
</P>
<P>
Sources said the move could be part of the July 10 Lusaka
cease-fire agreement aimed at ending the year-old civil war in the
Congo, the New Vision newspaper reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) stopped the flights
effective as from July 30, authority chief Ambrose Akandonda was
quoted as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He said that Air Alexander has been the main operator between
Entebbe and Kisangani, the third largest city in the Congo. The
company has since February been using a hush kitted Boeing 707
wet-leased (hired with crew) from a third country.
</P>
<P>
Akandonda said that Uganda, as a member of the International
Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO), has to abide by the rules of
the organization.
</P>
<P>
Any flights to the war zones would be in defiance of the
International Civil Aviation Organization rules, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kisangani in eastern Congo has no road link with Uganda. It
has been heavily depending on the goods from Kampala which are
flown there by Air Alexander. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
