<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hiroshima Marks 54th Anniversary of A-Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Hiroshima commemorated the 54th
anniversary of the atomic bombing of this southwestern Japanese
city Friday, while calling for the elimination of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
Some 50,000 people, including atomic bomb survivors, gathered
at the Peace Memorial Park near the center of the bombing, and
prayed for those who died from the world's first atomic bombing in
1945.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi, Hiroshima Mayor Tadatoshi
Akiba, and Pakistani Ambassador to Japan Touqir Hussain joined the
mourners at the annual Peace Memorial Ceremony.
</P>
<P>
At 8:15, the exact time of the blast, participants observed a
moment of silence, while representatives of A-bomb victims and
children tolled a bell of peace.
</P>
<P>
Akiba delivered a peace declaration in which he stressed the
need to have a strong will to abolish nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government should "understand fully the crucial
role" the A-bomb survivors have played in abolishing nuclear
weapons, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
Some 1,500 doves were released, while 300 children sang a song
of peace.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi also gave a speech at the ceremony, pledging that his
government will work toward nuclear nonproliferation and
disarmament and the eventual creation of a world free of nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
Obuchi said his government supports the proposal made by the
Tokyo forum on nuclear disarmament, which has urged the United
States and Russia to reduce the number of their strategic nuclear
warheads to 1,000 each.
</P>
<P>
Before the beginning of the ceremony, Hiroshima citizens
offered flowers and sticks of incense in front of the cenotaph at
the center of the park, praying for the repose of the victims'
souls.
</P>
<P>
The atomic bomb, which was dropped on Hiroshima on August 6,
1945, by the U.S. B-29 bomber "Enola Gay," killed an estimated 140,
000 people by the end of that year.
</P>
<P>
Akiba offered a new list of 5,071 atomic bomb victims who have
died since August 6 last year, bringing the death toll to 212,116.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
