<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Magic Accept Deal, Trade Hardaway to Suns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- He did not make it to the Los
Angeles Lakers, but three years later Penny Hardaway followed
Shaquille O'Neal out of Orlando.
</P>
<P>
Hardaway, who teamed with O'Neal to lead the Magic to the 1995
NBA Finals, today was traded to the Phoenix Suns in a sign-and-
trade deal. Those who headed to Orlando are forwards Danny Manning
and Pat Garrity, plus a pair of first-round picks.
</P>
<P>
Hardaway, a four-time All-Star, had three years left on his
contract with Orlando before exercising a clause that made him a
free agent, forcing the sign-and-trade deal. Terms were not
disclosed.
</P>
<P>
"I think we always tried to keep that window of opportunity
open for him to come back," Orlando general manager John Gabriel
said. "I think Penny looked at it as a pretty big challenge to
right some things that were not handled well on his part. Then it
was up to him to decide if he wanted to take on that challenge or
start over anew in Phoenix. That's what we wanted to do."
</P>
<P>
The Chicago Bulls made a similar move last season with Scottie
Pippen, who was sent to the Houston Rockets.
</P>
<P>
In Phoenix, Hardaway will team with Jason Kidd to form a dream
backourt. Hardaway has averaged more than 19 points, just under
five rebounds and over six assists per contest in his career.
</P>
<P>
Manning averaged 9.1 points and 4.4 rebounds off the bench. He
won the Sixth Man of the Year award in 1997-98, registering 13.5
points and 5.6 boards per game.
</P>
<P>
Garrity averaged 5.6 points in 39 games during his rookie
season.
</P>
<P>
"Clearly the goal for this franchise, No. 1 is to win a world
championship, still to win a world championship, even though it
may not come next year," Gabriel said. "The trading of Penny
Hardaway sets the foundation for the relaunching of this franchise
and this team."
</P>
<P>
The Suns were willing to deal two reserves instead of forward
Tom Gugliotta, who Orlando originally demanded. Gugliotta averaged
a team-leading 17 points and 8.9 rebounds a game last season.
</P>
<P>
The deal continued a very busy offseason for the Suns, who
agreed to terms with former Los Angeles Clippers forward Rodney
Rogers on Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rogers was the third free agent signed by the Suns, who inked
center Oliver Miller to a one-year deal and re-signed forward
Clifford Robinson to a reported four-year, $29 million package.
</P>
</TEXT>
