<HEADLINE> Yangtze River's Floodwaters Continue To Drop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The floodwaters on the Yangtze
River, China's longest, continue to drop from the dangerously-high
levels that lasted more than a month.
</P>
<P>
Water levels at the Chenglingji section in central-south China'
s Hunan Province, which is adjacent to one of the country's
largest freshwater lakes, Dongting Lake, dropped below the 33-
meter danger mark on Thursday afternoon. Sources at the local
hydrology station say that the lake water has been receding more
in the last two days.
</P>
<P>
Water levels at the Jiujiang section in east China's Jiangxi
Province were also lower than the previous day, but were still 1.
72 meters above the danger line yesterday afternoon and heavy
winds in the region has added pressure to the flood control effort.
Hydrology stations at the city of Jiujiang and at Poyang Lake
predict that waters will fall below the danger mark in about 10
days, meaning that the Yangtze's water levels are expected to last
some 40 days less than last year.
</P>
<P>
Pang Daomu, chief director of Hunan's Flood Control and Drought
Relief, says that the flooding on the Dongting Lake this year was
nearly as serious as the disaster last year but resulted in only
25 percent of the damage.
</P>
<P>
He attributes this achievement to the dyke reinforcement effort
since last year that cost some 6.2 billion yuan (747 million US
dollars) in Hunan. Moving some 140,000 people out of low-lying
areas near the lake to safer ground are also helped by the means
of increasing the flood containment area by some 16,000 hectares.
</P>
</TEXT>
