<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossilized Rhinoceros Skeleton Discovered in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered the fossilized skeleton of a large rhinoceros near the
Sala Us River in the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region, which they
believe to be some 50,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
The 3.5 meters long, 1.8 meters tall skeleton is the first
well-preserved skeleton of its kind to be discovered in China,
archeologists say.
</P>
<P>
An analysis of the teeth and bones prompted archaeologists to
guess that the adult rhinoceros must have fallen into river mud
and got drowned.
</P>
<P>
The Sala Us River area was the home of the Hetao Men, who lived
from around 35,000 to 50,000 years ago. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
