<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cardiovascular Disease Becomes Top Killer in Bulgaria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Statistics show that 62 percent of
the deaths in Bulgaria are caused by cardiovascular diseases, with
8,000 people dying annually of acute cardiac crisis.
</P>
<P>
The causes of death are the result of the unhealthy lifestyle
of Bulgarians and their negligence regarding health care, said
professor Choudomir Nachev, head of the Internal Diseases
Department at the Medical University of Sofia.
</P>
<P>
Bulgarians use 8-12 grams of salt per day, much more than the
recommended 4-6 grams. They also can fruit and vegetables instead
of eating fresh ones, so that excessive quantities of salt and
sugar are added to their foods.
</P>
<P>
A large number of Bulgarians check their blood pressure for
the first time at the age of 50-60, when they have -- as often as
not -- already developed hypertonia, Nachev said.
</P>
<P>
He recommended that Bulgarians accept stressful situations
calmly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
