<HEADLINE> Ancient Tomb Found in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
dug up a tomb that dates back to the Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-
24 A.D.) in China's Hebei Province.
</P>
<P>
They discovered a tomb passageway and coffin chamber at the
foot of Lingshan Mountain in Mancheng County where some
discoveries have been made previously. It is believed to contain
the remains of a high-ranking official.
</P>
<P>
The two-meter-wide passageway slopes downward for 15 meters and
the chamber is an eight-meter square that is 4.5 meters deep.
</P>
<P>
The archeologists say that the chamber has been broken into at
least three times and most burial objects have apparently been
stolen. The 40 relics dug up this time were mainly pottery and
bronzeware and jade, silver, and iron items, and ancient coins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
