<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB: Vietnam Needs 6.9b Dollars Investment in Energy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, August 6 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank (WB) has said that
Vietnam's energy sector faces four main challenges in making the
transition to a modern, industrialized society.
</P>
<P>
A press brief of the Would Bank in Vietnam issued on Thursday
said that Vietnam's economic growth is slowing because of the
financial crisis in East Asia, and because of its own inertia in
implementing structural and policy reforms.
</P>
<P>
Energy plays a crucial role in Vietnam's economic prospects,
said WB in the press brief, adding that Vietnam's energy sector is
facing following four main challenges:
</P>
<P>
First, to meet economic growth targets, energy supplies will
need to grow about 30 percent faster than GDP.
</P>
<P>
Second, though Vietnam is rich in natural resources, its
limited financial resources demand careful planning in the energy
sector.
</P>
<P>
Third, Vietnam will have to invest 5.3-5.5 percent of GDP --
twice the level of its Southeast Asian neighbors -- in essential
energy infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Fourth, attracting foreign investment will require creating an
enabling business environment, including a supportive legal
framework.
</P>
<P>
WB in its study said that Vietnam's power sector needs require
around 6.9 billion U.S. dollars in investment in the next three
years, and that a much more rational and coordinated approach is
needed among the state energy corporations covering gas, coal and
electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Montenegro Adopts Plan to Change Name of Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The government of the Republic
of Montenegro passed on Thursday a draft plan on name change aimed
at loosening its partnership with Serbia, reported Yugoslavia's
Tanjug news agency.
</P>
<P>
The plan proposes that the name of the Federal Republic of
Yugoslavia be changed into the Commonwealth of States of
Montenegro and Serbia, Montenegro Prime Minister Filip Vujanovic
told the press.
</P>
<P>
The plan proposes replacing the current federal government with
a "council of ministers" and the current two-chamber Yugoslav
parliament with a single house, said Vujanovic, who is supported
by the West.
</P>
<P>
It also calls for the abolition of the central foreign ministry
and the establishment of two separate foreign ministries instead.
</P>
<P>
Diplomats here said that the plan, which is going to be
presented to the parliament of Montenegro and the government of
Serbia, is a result of the West isolation policy on Serbia, which,
with Montenegro, formed the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia in
April, 1992 after the former Yugoslavia fell apart.
</P>
<P>
On July 19, The European Union decided to lift its air and oil
embargo on Montenegro, but to continue the embargo on Serbia.
</P>
<P>
On July 30, the summit on the Balkan Stability Pact held in
Sarajevo worked out the concrete measures to assist Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton has told Vujanovic that Washington
will provide 10 million U.S. dollars to the opposition to the
Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
Clinton has stressed that as long as Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic is in power, the isolation policy will continue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
