<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brazil Looks Sharp in Pan Am Pool </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian swimmers
still look sharp in the Pan Am Pool here on Thursday, scooping up
a pair of golds and establishing a Games record.
</P>
<P>
A brazilian quartet of Fernando Scherer, Cesar Qintaes, Andre
Cordeiro and Gustavo Borges set a pounding pace to the gold medal
and the new Pan Am best time of 3:17.18, eclipsing more than one
seconds off the previous 3:18.68.
</P>
<P>
The United States was a distant second in 3:19.00 and Venezuela
the third in 3:22.21.
</P>
<P>
In the men's 400m freestyle race, Brazilian Luiz Lima clocked 3:
52.25 to chalk up the gold, the fifth following their hatrick
performances yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The traditional power United States, from which lots of first-
choice stars are absent to concentrate on the Pan Pacific Games
championships later this month in Sydney, still managed two golds
today.
</P>
<P>
Staciana Stitts shattered the Games record to win women's 100m
breastroke in 1:09.16 while in the women's 100m butterfly, Karen
Campbell registered a 1:00.05 clocking to beat off Canadian double
gold medallist Jessica Deglau for the title.
</P>
<P>
But another home swimmer delighted the delirious sold-out crowd
as Morgan Knabe set a new Games record of 2:14.73 to take out the
men's 200m breastroke event.
</P>
<P>
In the Pan Am tennis competitions which wrapped up here today,
Brazil pairs made it a sweep victory as both men's and women's
titles fell to their hands.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela's Maria Vento continued her giantkilling way by
scoring a 7-6 (7-3), 6-1 victory over American second seed Tara
Synder to take the women's title. Vento upset 6-0, 6-3 wimbledon
semifinalist Alexandra Stevenson in yesterday's semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
Men's final was an all-American affair won by Paul Goldstein 6-
4, 0-6, 3-6 over the tournament's top seed Cecil Mamiit.
</P>
<P>
In the women's soccer final, the United States edged Mexico 1-0
for the gold.
</P>
<P>
In the medals count, Americans looked unshakable at the top
place with 87 golds, with Cuba (53) and Canada (49) following
behind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
