<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Approves Final Bill on Tax Cut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Republican-controlled U.S.
Congress on Thursday approved the final bill to cut 792 billion U.
S. dollars in taxes in the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
President Bill Clinton has vowed to veto the bill, saying that
it would squander bigger-than-expected budget surpluses and
threaten the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
The bill, proposed by Republicans but opposed by Democrats,
would trim all five income tax rates by one percentage point,
lower capital gains taxes for individuals, eliminate estate taxes
and ease the so-called marriage-tax penalty.
</P>
<P>
Clinton advisers warned that it would force automatic cuts in a
wide range of critical government programs, including Medicare.
</P>
<P>
Undeterred, the Senate gave the measure final approval in a
mostly party-line vote of 50 to 49. The House of Representatives
passed it earlier by a 221-206 vote.
</P>
<P>
Republican leaders were expected to send the bill to Clinton in
September, after Congress takes its August recess. That will give
Republicans a chance to sell the plan to their constituents before
it is vetoed.
</P>
<P>
Tax cuts are a key political battleground for Republicans and
Democrats, and both parties expect Thursday's vote to resonate in
the 2000 presidential and congressional races.
</P>
<P>
At 792 billion dollars, the Republican bill promises the
largest tax cut since 1981 when Ronald Reagan was president.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and congressional Democrats say they favor targeted tax
breaks in the 250 billion to 300 billion dollar range as part of a
broader agreement to shore up the Social Security Retirement
system and the Medicare Health Care program.
</P>
<P>
Under the Republican tax bill, income tax rates would be
reduced to 14 percent, 27 percent, 30 percent, 35 percent and 38.6
percent from 15 percent, 28 percent, 31 percent, 36 percent and 39.
6 percent. For families in the lowest bracket, the measure would
provide a 7 percent tax break. Wealthier taxpayers would get a 4
percent break.
</P>
<P>
The bill would also cut the top capital gains tax rate on
investment profits for individuals to 18 percent from 20 percent,
effective January 1, 1999, and reduce the capital gains rate for
taxpayers in the lowest income tax bracket to 8 percent from 10
percent. Capital gains would be indexed for inflation under the
plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian PM: No Federal Intervention on Fuel Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister John
Howard Friday ruled out federal intervention to curb rising fuel
prices, saying it was simply the market in operation and prices
would eventually settle.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, Howard said he could understand that
consumers paying more than 80 Australian cents (52.8 U.S. cents )
a liter might be angry.
</P>
<P>
But he said Australia still enjoyed very low fuel prices by
world standard, second only to the United States and substantially
lower than Europe.
</P>
<P>
The fuel price increases in Australian have been dramatic, up
from under 70 Australian cents (46.2 U.S. cents) a liter for
unleaded petrol in March to more than 80 Australian cents (52.8
U.S. cents) in some places.
</P>
<P>
Australian Competition and Consumer Commission chairman Allan
Fels said Thursday the hike was due to countries of the
Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) pushing
up their oil prices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mercosur Looks for Solution to Internal Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Southern Common Market (
Mercosur) will search for a way to solve its worst financial
crisis since its founding in 1991.
</P>
<P>
During the extraordinary meeting of the common market group on
Thursday and Friday in the Uruguayan capital, technical
negotiators from Argentina, Brazil, Paraguay and Uruguay discussed
the trade controversies between Argentina and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
The negotiators are also preparing for a meeting of Mercosur's
Council of Ministers on Friday in which ministers will design the
future of the bloc's customs union.
</P>
<P>
Argentina's recent announcement of excluding member countries
of Mercosur from safeguard measures calmed the heated discussion.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Argentina enacted a protocol regarding
macro-economic coordination, which sets contingency measures when
trade balances and fluctuations become seriously distorted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Brazil said it would not provide financial
compensation for products of its associate members due to the
devaluation of Brazil's currency.
</P>
<P>
Uruguay insisted on strengthening Mercosur by creating a
mechanism that would control macro-economic policies and resolves
trade disputes.
</P>
<P>
Paraguay told Mercosur that it would not propose revising the
Asuncion Treaty, but Paraguayan industrialists are asking for
revisions of this organizations legal norms, arguing that
differences between Argentina and Brazil have damaged the bloc's
ability to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
Trade disputes between Argentina and Brazil occurred after
Argentina notified Brazil about enacting safeguard measures
against Brazilian products.
</P>
<P>
Although Argentina quickly canceled restrictive measures
against products from Mercosur countries, the turbulence caused
within the bloc by the action has not subsided.
</P>
<P>
Uruguayan President Julio Maria Sanguinetti said that in the
final analysis, the Argentina-Brazil trade quarrel is due to a
Latin American economic recession, and therefore the problem must
be attacked at its roots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0286 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Family Income Dropped 4 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Italian family income dropped more
than 4 percent in real terms in the period from 1991 to 1998,
while fiscal pressure has risen 10 percent this year, statistics
released Thursday by representatives of Italy's retail association
Confcommercio showed.
</P>
<P>
The disposable income for an average Italian family dropped 4.4
percent in this period, while in the same time consumption grew 6.
8 percent and income taxes rose 45.2 percent, according to the
association.
</P>
<P>
It also found that prices for essential goods, including
housing, water, electric power, telephone, health, transport and
insurance, rose by an average of 9.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Costs for health care rose by 0.9 percent to 3.2 percent in
1998, while social services jumped 13 percent and water costs up 9.
2 percent.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to liberalization of the market, the merchants' group
reported that communication prices dropped by 21.1 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
