<HEADLINE> China's Young Scientist Awarded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Organizers of the first
nationwide award for Chinese students sponsored by a foreign
company pledged Thursday to encourage more high-school students to
study science and broaden their knowledge, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
At the award ceremony for the 7th Rado Chinese Youth Talent
Contest held yesterday at Beijing University, Rado vice-president
Eric Steiner said that his company will continue promoting
activities with a philosophy of "challenging the future."
</P>
<P>
Forty students were selected from 900 participants nationwide
for the final, which included tests in Chinese, computing and
creativity plus mathematics, physics and chemistry competitions.
Four categories of prizes were awarded.
</P>
<P>
The four first-prize winners each received 10,000 yuan (1,210 U.
S.dollars) as well as a chance to visit Switzerland in September.
</P>
<P>
The award was initiated in 1993 by Swiss watchmaker Rado in
collaboration with science institutions in Beijing, Shanghai and
Guangdong and Hong Kong New Generation Culture Association. Most
winners are now studying at China's prestigious Beijing and
Qinghua universities.
</P>
<P>
Steiner said the contest offers an ideal combination to
encourage Chinese students to invest their talent for the benefit
of China and their own personal career, according to the paper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0289 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Says Not to Intervene in Colombian Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QUITO, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Ecuador's armed forces said
Thursday they will not participate in regional armed intervention
headed by the United States against Colombian guerrillas or drug
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
The joint command of Ecuador's armed forces said in a
communique that U.S. soldiers frequently train in Ecuador for
jungle combat, but this does not mean the country will participate
in a regional strategy against the guerrillas or drug traffickers
in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
According to the Colombian daily "El Espectador," special
American forces are training in a jungle school operated by the
Ecuadorian Army to fight guerrillas in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
The joint command said Ecuador's armed forces will guarantee
the control of the border with Colombia to prevent the
infiltration of Colombia's guerrillas into the country of Ecuador.
</P>
</TEXT>
