<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nicaragua to Evacuate 16,000 Persons Living Near Volcano </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANAGUA, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The Nicaraguan government is
intensifying the evacuation of around 16,000 people living very
near to volcano Cerro Negro, which erupted Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The volcano erupted again at 10 o'clock local time (1600 GMT),
after provoking a large quantity of quakes with top intensity of 4.
7 degrees on the Richter scale, confirmed the Nicaraguan
authorities.
</P>
<P>
According to officials and journalists that got close to the
volcano, Cerro Negro now has three new craters on the east side,
by which it throws out ash, sand and sometimes a little lava,
forming a huge "mushroom" of about 5,000 meters height.
</P>
<P>
Inhabitants of municipalities around Cerro Negro are now
protecting themselves with sombreros, caps or berets, and
handkerchiefs on their faces, while receiving urgent advice on
protection against eventual gas emanations.
</P>
<P>
The mayor of Leon, with 161,530 residents 100 kilometers west
of Managua, Rigoberto Sampsom, decreed "red alert" and went to an
area where he ordered evacuating about 16,000 peasants from eight
communities near the volcano. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
