<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's International Reserves Reach Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's international
reserves reached last Friday the record high level of 31.421
billion U.S. dollars, the Bank of Mexico announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The reserves registered a sharp increase of 1.127 billion
dollars in the last three weeks, which included means coming from
a credit given by the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The press here on the same day quoted Gulllermo Perry, chief
economist for Latin America of the World Bank, as saying that
Mexico was following the right monetary policy and has obtained
evident results.
</P>
<P>
"Mexico and Peru are the two Latin American countries which
responded best to the Asian and Brazilian crises," Perry said,
citing the flexible exchange rate policy the Mexican government
has adhered to since the 1994 peso devaluation as the backbone of
economic rebound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
