<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 280 Hot spots Detected in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A preliminary survey has shown
that there are more than 280 hot spots in West Kalimantan
province, Indonesia, putting the area in a real danger of being
covered by thick haze, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
State Minister for the Environment Panangian Siregar said
Thursday in Pontianak, capital of West Kalimantan that he had seen
part of the hot spots from the plane, Antara News Agency reported
Friday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said when his plane flew over Sintang District in
the province, he saw people on the ground burning scrubs in small
areas, apparently for the purpose of clearing land.
</P>
<P>
Haze, which always blankets some areas in West Kalimantan
during the dry season, could grow into an international problem if
the haze spreads to neighboring countries like Brunei and
Malaysia, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the past, the haze did spread to those countries and they
promptly lodged complaints because the vapor created such problems
as reduced visibility and air pollution, Panangian said.
</P>
<P>
He said if the burning of scrubs was done by big companies, the
government would immediately take strong measures against them.
But so far, it seemed that the burning was the work of members of
local community.
</P>
<P>
Some experts said this year's forest fires may be bigger than
that in 1997 when forest fires raged in many parts of the islands
of Sumatra and Kalimantan.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 fires destroyed about 5 million hectares of forest in
the country with an economic lose of about 4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Another report said, people in Sumatra's province of Riau were
urged Thursday to wear masks and reduce outdoor activities because
haze from forest fires now covering the region has hit a dangerous
level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xie, Galliamova Deadlocked at World Chess Championship </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAZAN, Russia, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Xie Jun of China failed to
extend her lead as she lost to Galliamova of Russia at the sixth
round of the world women's chess championship on Thursday here.
</P>
<P>
Xie, who moved first with white pieces, could not resist the
charge of Galliamova and bowed out at the 49th move.
</P>
<P>
Both players have been locked in a seesaw showdown as they
tallied the equal record with two wins, two losses and two draws
after six rounds.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds are remained for the Russian leg with the next eight
rounds contested at Shenyang,a northeast China city from August
13 to 25.
</P>
<P>
As is regulated by the FIDE, the chess world ruling body,
either player who first collected 8.5 points will be the winner
and the play-off is needed if both sides tie 8-all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
