<P>
WELLINGTON, August 6 (Xinhua) -- A total of 146 pilots of the
Ansett New Zealand, an airline owned by Australians but operating
in New Zealand, walked off the job as of four o'clock Friday
morning for a 24-hour strike.
</P>
<P>
The pilots are striking over what they said are Ansett plans to
save 5 million NZ dollars (2.7 million U.S. dollars) a year by
cutting pilot numbers by at least 30, according to the New Zealand
 Press Association (NZPA).
</P>
<P>
The strike has forced the cancellation of 100 Ansett flights in
the country. Pilots have also given notice of two more 24-hour
strikes, one next Tuesday and the other the following Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Arch-rival Air New Zealand is cashing in on the Ansett strike,
putting on eight extra flights between Auckland, Wellington,
Christchurch and Queenstown. The latter two cities are on New
Zealand's South Islands.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
