<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stevenson Upset about Pan Am Semi Defeat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 5 (Xinhua) -- Wimbledon semifinalist
Alexandra Stevenson admitted yesterday's semi-final crushing
defeat at the Winnipeg Law Tennis Club made her very down.
</P>
<P>
"I think I feel disappointed in myself and myself as an
American player. I really wanted the gold," the 19-year-old
American tennis prospect said of her 6-0, 6-3 loss to Venezuela's
Maria Vento in the Pan Am women's tennis semi-finals on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"But the Olympics is in 10 months and I'll just have to aim for
that." she said.
</P>
<P>
The much-hyped Stevenson, who is ranked No.37 in the world and
argueably the biggest star in the Winnipeg Games, will have to
settle for a bronze medal. The Pan Am competition setup doesn't
require losers of the semis to go head to head for third place.
</P>
<P>
Stevenson insisted all the hype surrounding her Wimbledon
victory and the notoriety of being NBA legend Julius Erving's
biological daughter hasn't bothered her on the court.
</P>
<P>
"I only got to the semis of Wimbledon and the semis here so
that means I have a lot of work ahead of me," she said.
</P>
<P>
The Pan Am Games was her first tournament since last month's
Wimbledon Open where she made history by becoming the first
qualifier in the history of the coveted tournament to reach women'
s singles semi-finals.
</P>
<P>
The American teenager said she had an upset stomach prior to
the match. "I just made errors," she said, "I was late to the ball
and when you're dizzy you have to play tough. I tried to do that
but it didn't work out."
</P>
<P>
Promoted by her mother Samantha, a freelance journalist and an
unofficial co-ordinator of the US delegation, Stevenson creditted
vento.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan had been ranked as high as 31 (currently 117)
and got to the fourth round of the 1997 French Open.
</P>
<P>
"I was able to move her around a lot and try to make her have a
lot of unforced errors which she did," said Vento, 25. "I feel
really good about this win."
</P>
<P>
Vento and American Tara Snyder will go for women's gold later
today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990806.0315 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Bank Keeps Interest Rates on Hold </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON August 5 (Xinhua) - The Bank of England has decided to
leave UK interest rates unchanged at 5 percent, despite signs of
the quickening pace of economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
It is the second month in succession that members of the bank's
Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) have voted for no change in rates,
which remain at a 22-year low.
</P>
<P>
The decision came as no surprise to economists, although many
of them believe it is now only a matter of time before the MPC
starts raising rates again to head off inflation as the recovery
gathers strength.
</P>
<P>
It also came as a relief for those with mortgages and is
welcomed by business leaders who feared that a rise in rates could
push up the value of the pound and so make life tougher for
exporters.
</P>
<P>
The MPC's brief is to set interest rates to ensure that
underlying inflation stays within 1 percent of the 2.5 percent
target rate on inflation. It currently stands at 2.2 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
