<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flying Doctors Perform Eye Operations in Gansu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, August 6 (Xinhua) -- Doctors from Orbis, an airborne
eye hospital traveling around the world, have completed 72 eye
operations in this capital of northwest China's Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
It is the 24th mission to China for the Orbis doctors and
nurses, who come from 11 countries, including India, the United
States, Britain and Canada.
</P>
<P>
The three weeks of free surgery has helped local people regain
their eyesight through cataract removal, implanting of corneas,
and glaucoma treatment. The doctors also conducted 10 operations
as training programs at a local hospital, and donated nine corneas.
</P>
<P>
Harish Nayak, chief ophthalmologist of Orbis, described their
activities in Lanzhou as a successful mission which has laid a
good foundation for future cooperation.
</P>
<P>
More than 80 local medical personnel attended the operations
and received training courses in a bid to improve local
ophthalmologic services.
</P>
<P>
As a sign of the importance it attaches to its collaboration
with China, Orbis set up its China branch in Shanghai recently, as
well as an ophthalmologic training center in Taiyuan, capital of
Shanxi Province, said Dr. Nayak.
</P>
<P>
Since its establishment in 1982, Orbis has accomplished more
than 390 medical missions to 79 countries, conducting operations
and training programs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
