<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030GMT, August 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Syrian President Hafez al-Assad has replied to
President Bill Clinton on resumption of peace talks between Syria
and Israel, the White House said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
President Assad's letter was received on Wednesday at the White
House, which was in response to last month letter, in which
Clinton urged Assad to "seize the moment of opportunity" and
negotiate peace terms with Israel's newly elected prime minister,
Ehud Barak. (US-Syria-Assad)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The U.S. State Department on Thursday warned
American citizens around the world to take precaution as the first
anniversary of two U.S. embassy bombings in Africa was drawing
nearer. (US-Embassy Bombing-Warning)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Thursday that it was
concerned over a "rising tide" of violence in Indonesia's Aceh
province.
</P>
<P>
"The United States is deeply concerned about the rising tide of
violence which has claimed over a hundred lives in recent months
and dramatically increased tensions in the Indonesian province of
Aceh," State Department spokesman James Rubin said in a written
statement. (US-Indonesia-Violence)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States Thursday released about 40 top
secret documents held by the Soviet Union about the assassination
of former U.S. President John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
The documents show that Kennedy's wife, Jacqueline Kennedy,
wrote to Soviet leader Nikita Khrushchev nine days after her
husband's assassination, saying the U.S. policy of "restraint"
would continue. (US-Russia-Kennedy)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- The South African apartheid regime's chief
assassin, Eugene de Kock, was Thursday granted amnesty by the
Truth and Reconciliation Commission (TRC) for the 1988 bombing of
Khotso House, the headquarters of the South African Council of
Churches.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time the former commander of the Vlakplaas
police unit, which used murder and torture to defend white rule,
has been pardoned for any of his crimes for which he is serving
several life sentences. (SAfrica-Assassin-Amnesty)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LAGOS -- The president of Nigeria's 109-member Senate, Evan
Enwerem, Thursday branded allegations against him as "wicked
fabrication and calculated attempt" to tarnish his image.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in Abuja, the third in the
hierarchy in the west African nation dismissed the letter
purportedly signed by the Chief Secretary to the Premier of the
defunct eastern Nigeria describing him as a convict as "a forgery".
(Nigeria-Senate President)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States argued on Thursday that it was
reasonable that ethnic Albanians take violent revenge against
Serbs but unreasonable to expect NATO to protect all Serbs.
</P>
<P>
"It shouldn't be a surprise to anyone... Albanian people of
Kosovo -- when the Albanians were freed from these shackles, that
there would be the potential for revenge and retaliation against
Serbs," State Department spokesman James Rubin told a regular
briefing. (US-Kosovo-NATO)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WELLINGTON -- A total of 146 pilots of the Ansett New Zealand,
an airline owned by Australians but operating in New Zealand,
walked off the job as of four o'clock Friday morning for a 24-hour
strike. (New Zealand-Pilot Strike) 
</P>
