<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USA Becomes Pharmacy for World's Sports Cheaters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WINNIPEG, Canada, August 5 (Xinhua) -- The United States seems
to be becoming the pharmacy for world-wide sports cheaters.
</P>
<P>
Nandrolone, an anabolic steroid found in the urine of Canadian
roller hockey goalie Steve Vezina at the Pan Am Games last week,
seems to be the drug of the moment.
</P>
<P>
But it's not because drug testing has become more sophisticated
or because researchers have discovered some new methods of
discovering prohibited substances, said Christiane Ayotte,
director of a Montreal laboratory accredited by the International
Olympic Committee (IOC).
</P>
<P>
It's because it's easy to get steroid precursors through oral
supplements in the United States, the only country in the world
that allows the sale of these substances. The precursors turn into
steroids when metabolized by the body.
</P>
<P>
The US Food and Drug Administration will not regulate the use
of steroid precursors unless there is clear proof that they work
to increase muscle mass, Ayotte said.
</P>
<P>
Nandrolone is used by the agriculture industry to increase the
muscle mass of beef cattle. But word came yesterday that Linford
Chiristie, a 39-year-old athlete who has always spoken out against
drug use, was suspended for testing positive for Nandrolone.
</P>
<P>
It seems that more athletes are being caught lately, Ayotte
said, because many of them are high-profile and catch a lot more
attention. " I don't think the number of positive tests has
increased," she said.
</P>
<P>
And the top athletes have been caught because they have been
turning to the steroid precursors that are freely available in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
Nandrolone is a steroid usually available as an injectible
medication that requires a doctor's prescription, Ayotte said.
Some athletes may get it through the black market or from a doctor
who is very lenient in making out prescriptions for it.
</P>
<P>
Now it's much easier to buy the precursor of the drug in the
United States. The precursor is administered orally.
</P>
<P>
The IOC and countries that do not allow the sale of such
substances are putting pressure on the United States to change its
rules, Ayotte said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
